10 1 1 179 According to this L.A. Times story (which credits the team-owned flagship radio station), the Angels have <MENTION CHAIN="1">made</MENTION> an eight-year offer to free agent first baseman Mark Teixeira.
10 1 2 180 The dollar amount was unspecified, but Bill Shaikin, the fine reporter who wrote the story, says the team was believed to have offered at least $160 million.
10 1 3 181 This, obviously, changes the landscape of the Teixeira sweepstakes, as the Nationals' best chance for landing him was to blow everyone else out of the water with their offer -- which, apparently, has not happened.
10 1 4 182 That's not to say the Nationals cannot sweeten their offer, but team officials have indicated an unwillingness to get into a bidding war with higher-revenue teams.
10 1 5 183 Of course, we still have yet to hear from the Red Sox -- or even the Yankees, as I hypothesized in today's print edition. 
10 1 6 184 In any case, it appears this thing is far from over.
10 2 1 185 Angels general manager Tony Reagins <MENTION CHAIN="2">confirmed</MENTION> to the Los Angeles Times that he has <MENTION CHAIN="1">made</MENTION> an eight-year offer to free agent first baseman Mark Teixeira.
10 2 2 186 Regains didn't reveal the dollar amounts, but the newspaper speculates the deal is worth at least $160 million.
10 2 3 187 Teixeira is considered the top offensive player available on the free agent market, and the Orioles (seven years, $140-$150 million) and Nationals (eight years, $160 million) reportedly have made sizeable offers as well.
10 2 4 188 The Red Sox, considered to be the front-runner for Teixeira, also have put in a bid, though monetary details have been kept quiet.
10 2 5 189 There has been talk of the Yankees being in the Teixeira sweepstakes as well.
10 2 6 190 Teixeira, 28, has hit at least 30 homers and driven in at least 105 runs in each of the past five seasons.
10 2 7 191 After being acquired from the Braves before the trading deadline this past season, Teixeira hit .358 with 13 homers and 43 RBIs in 54 games with the Angels.
10 3 1 192 The Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim <MENTION CHAIN="1">offered</MENTION> free-agent first baseman Mark Teixeira an eight-year contract at the Winter Meetings in Las Vegas.
10 3 2 193 Owner Arte Moreno met with Scott Boras, Teixeira's agent, and presented him with the offer, which is believed to be worth at least $160 million and possibly as much as $180 million over the life of the contract.
10 3 3 194 ``It's something they can consider - or should consider,'' Angels general manager Tony Reagins told MLB.com on Friday. 
10 3 4 195 ``They have the right.''
10 3 5 196 Other teams in the battle for Teixeira are the Baltimore Orioles (seven years, $140-150 million), Washington Nationals (eight years, $160 million) and Boston Red Sox.
10 3 6 197 The New York Yankees also have expressed interest.
10 3 7 198 Teixeira, 28, was acquired by the Angels in a July 29 deal with the Atlanta Braves last season and hit 13 home runs and 43 RBIs in 54 games.
10 3 8 199 Overall, he finished the season with a .308 average, 33 homers and 121 RBI.
10 3 9 200 It marked the fifth straight 30-homer, 100-RBI season for Teixeira.
10 3 10 201 He batted .467 with seven hits and four walks in the American League Division Series as the Angels fell to the Red Sox in four games.
10 4 1 202 The Angels have <MENTION CHAIN="1">offered</MENTION> an eight-year contract to Mark Teixeira, general manager Tony Reagins <MENTION CHAIN="2">said</MENTION> Friday night.
10 4 2 203 The contract would be the longest and richest in club history.
10 4 3 204 The value could almost double the previous club record, the $90 million guaranteed last year to Torii Hunter.
10 4 4 205 Reagins declined to provide the value of Teixeira's offer.
10 4 5 206 The Angels are believed to have offered at least $160 million, matching or exceeding the highest offer so far reported for Teixeira.
10 4 6 207 Owner Arte Moreno flew from his Arizona home to Las Vegas on Tuesday and met personally with Scott Boras, the agent for Teixeira.
10 4 7 208 Angels spokesman Tim Mead said he believed Moreno presented the offer to Boras at that time.
10 4 8 209 Mead also said he did not know when the offer might expire.
10 4 9 210 None of the other teams in the Teixeira sweepstakes -- the Boston Red Sox, Baltimore Orioles and Washington Nationals -- has been reported to have offered more than eight years.
10 4 10 211 The Nationals reportedly have bid $160 million over eight years, the Orioles between $140 million and $150 million over seven years.
10 4 11 212 The details of the Boston bid have not been reported.
10 4 12 213 The Angels had exclusive negotiating rights with Teixeira for the first 15 days after the World Series, but they declined to make an offer during that time and said they would do so at an appropriate time.
10 4 13 214 Boras has had one month since then to solicit bids from other teams, enabling him to let Moreno know how the market had developed and enabling Moreno to make his first -- and perhaps only -- offer without Boras shopping that offer to other teams.
10 4 14 215 The Angels have not wavered from treating Teixeira as their top priority, even as other coveted options have evaporated.
10 4 15 216 The Angels negotiated with pitcher CC Sabathia, a favorite among their scouts, but they chose not to make an offer after deciding they would not match the New York Yankees' initial $140-million bid.
10 4 16 217 Sabathia agreed to a seven-year, $161-million deal with the Yankees late Tuesday night, hours after Moreno met with Boras.
10 4 17 218 On Friday, outfielder Raul Ibanez signed a three-year, $31.5-million contract with the Philadelphia Phillies.
10 4 18 219 The Angels had considered signing Ibanez if they lost out on Teixeira, with Ibanez playing left field and Kendry Morales replacing Teixeira at first base.
10 4 19 220 The Angels' eight-year offer first was reported Friday night on the team-owned radio station, AM 830.
10 5 1 221 Super-agent Scott Boras said leaving the Winter Meetings that it was going to take an eight-year deal to get the services of slugging first-baseman Mark Teixeira.
10 5 2 222 The Angels apparently are good with that.
10 5 3 223 Los Angeles general manager Tony Reagins has sounded like a broken record <MENTION CHAIN="2">saying</MENTION> that resigning Teixeira was his top priority, and backed that up now with an eight-year <MENTION CHAIN="1">offer</MENTION>.
10 5 4 224 No dollar figures have been released with the offer, but the seven-year offers for Teixeira were in the $140 million to $160 million range and the new offer is expected to be at the top of that range.
10 5 5 225 If accepted, this would certainly be the largest contract in the Angels history, dwarfing the four-year, $90 million deal that Torii Hunter got just last summer.
10 5 6 226 But if he keeps mashing like he did after the trade, Teixeira could be worth the bank.
10 5 7 227 In 54 games with the Angeles he hit .358 with 13 home runs and 43 RBIs, and had a slugging percentage of .632.
10 5 8 228 The two-time Gold Glove winner also helped solidify the Angeles infield.
10 5 9 229 After the Winter Meetings, the conventional wisdom was that the Red Sox were the frontrunners for Teixeira's services, even though they met privately and their offer was never made public (maybe that's why people thought they were the leaders).
10 5 10 230 However, no other offer (including from the Nationals and Oriels trying to bring Teixeira back to his native Maryland) was thought to be more than seven years.
10 5 11 231 The race for Teixeira seems to be in the final furlong.
10 5 12 232 But then again, Boras is a patient man, especially if he thinks more money could be around the corner.
