11 1 1 257 The 4th parliamentary election of Turkmenistan <MENTION CHAIN="1">ended</MENTION> Sunday evening as scheduled, <MENTION CHAIN="5">said</MENTION> reports from Ashgabat, Turkmenistan's capital.
11 1 2 258 More than 2,000 booths in 125 constituencies in the country were closed at 6:00 p.m. local time (1300 GMT).
11 1 3 259 The Central Election and Referendum Commission declared the election valid. 
11 1 4 260 Official election results will be announced within 10 days.
11 1 5 261 Some 2.44 million people, accounting for some 88.41 percent of the country's eligible voters, cast their ballots as of 4:00 p.m. local time (1100 GMT).
11 1 6 262 Under Turkmen laws, parliamentary elections can only be declared valid with a turnout more than 50 percent of eligible voters.
11 1 7 263 The election attracted wide attention as it was held amid constitutional and justice reforms advocated by President Kurbanguly Berdymukhamedov.
11 1 8 264 About 40 observers from the United Nations, the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe and the Commonwealth of Independent States oversaw the election.
11 1 9 265 This was the first the government allowed international observers to supervise the elections in Turkmenistan.
11 1 10 266 Berdymukhamedov said earlier that the parliamentary elections in Turkmenistan would show the international community that the country's democratization process is irreversible with the adoption of a new constitution.
11 10 1 267 Voting for MPs to Majlis (Parliament) <MENTION CHAIN="1">began</MENTION> in Turkmenistan on Dec.14.
11 10 2 268 A total of 288 candidates run for 125 parliamentary seats, with 37 of the candidates registered in the capital city of Turkmenistan - Ashgabat, 46 in Akhal region, 25 in Balkan region, 63 in Dashoguz region, 56 in Lebap region, and 61 in Mary region.
11 10 3 269 Of the 288 candidates, 286 have higher education, 202 are under 45 years old, and 56 are women.
11 10 4 270 Turkmenistan has 27 polling stations abroad attached to the country's diplomatic missions.
11 10 5 271 Elections take place by the voting of Turkmenistan citizens on the basis of a universal, equal and direct suffrage with secret ballot and alternative basis.
11 10 6 272 The term of office of MPs is five years.
11 10 7 273 For the first time foreign observers and experts, representatives from European states and international organizations including UN, OSCE, and CIS Executive Committee monitor elections in Turkmenistan.
11 11 1 274 Voters in Turkmenistan <MENTION CHAIN="1">began</MENTION> to cast their ballots at 8: 00 am local time ( 0300 GMT ) on Sunday in the country's fourth parliamentary election, <MENTION CHAIN="5">said</MENTION> reports from Ashgabat, Turkmenistan's capital.
11 11 2 275 Over 2.5 million Turkmens are eligible to vote at more than 2,000 booths in the country, while there are 27 overseas booths.
11 11 3 276 Voting will close at 6: 00 p.m. local time (1300 GMT) Sunday.
11 11 4 277 In accordance with the country's election law, there are a total of 125 contituencies in the current election and single winners will be elected in each of them for a term of five years.
11 11 5 278 A total of 288 candidates are vying for the 125 seats in the legislature.
11 2 1 279 Turkmenistan <MENTION CHAIN="1">voted</MENTION> Sunday in a parliamentary election meant to show that the energy-rich central Asian nation was shedding its autocratic past, but Western observers <MENTION CHAIN="2">said</MENTION> nothing had changed.
11 2 2 280 Authorities said turnout reached 93.87 percent in the election for 288 candidates, all of whom support the policies of President Gurbanguly Berdymukhamedov in the ex-Soviet republic.
11 2 3 281 Voting stations were festooned with Turkmen flags and pictures of Berdymukhamedov, the successor of eccentric dictator Saparmurat Niyazov, who ruled Turkmenistan for two decades until his death in 2006.
11 2 4 282 Over 2.5 million people were eligible to vote in the election, held under the framework of a new constitution approved in September and intended to increase parliament's powers and raise the number of seats from 65 to 125.
11 2 5 283 ``I attach hopes for the better to these elections, especially for our children,'' Valentina Redzhepova, an official at one of Ashgabat's voting precincts, told AFP.
11 2 6 284 ``We are waiting for borders to open even further so more guests can come to us and so we can visit them.''
11 2 7 285 Voters, however, appeared reluctant to criticise the government.
11 2 8 286 In Gyami, a village outside the Turkmen capital, 25-year-old Guzel said she had come to the local polling station to vote and watch her daughter perform in a children's folk-dance troupe.
11 2 9 287 ``I voted for our fellow village resident.
11 2 10 288 He is an experienced person and knows village life well,'' she said.
11 2 11 289 Pensioner Bayram-aga, a voter in Ashgabat, said:
11 2 12 290 ``I remember the elections from the Soviet days. ...
11 2 13 291 People were very active then, it was like a festival.
11 2 14 292 Now it's much quieter.''
11 2 15 293 Western observers say Niyazov still casts a shadow, despite promises of openness by Berdymukhamedov and some moves to dismantle the late dictator's bizarre personality cult.
11 2 16 294 Niyazov's gold statue still towers over the desert nation's capital, rotating to face the sun.
11 2 17 295 ``The facade has changed but the foundations remain the same,'' said a Western diplomat, who requested anonymity.
11 2 18 296 ``Power rests entirely with the president.
11 2 19 297 His photo appears every day on the front of the papers.
11 2 20 298 He strictly controls the economy and the whole of the media,'' the diplomat added.
11 2 21 299 New York-based Human Rights Watch said in an assessment last month that Turkmenistan had made ``some progress'' but ``remains ... one of the most repressive and authoritarian states in the world.''
11 2 22 300 The elections are unlikely to get a clean bill of health from the West, not least as all candidates have stressed support for the president while campaigning.
11 2 23 301 The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe sent eight experts to monitor the poll and draw up an ``internal report.''
11 2 24 302 The group's spokesman, Jens Hagen Eschenbecher, told AFP that the experts would not be making any public statements on their conclusions.
11 2 25 303 Ninety percent of the 288 candidates come from the Democratic Party set up by Niyazov in place of the Communist Party, with the other 10 percent coming from so-called ``initiative groups'' that have little clout.
11 2 26 304 All candidates are funded by the state, with a ban on other funding.
11 2 27 305 Western journalists have been refused permission to cover the vote.
11 2 28 306 Foreign election observers will mainly come from the Commonwealth of Independent States, a post-Soviet group with little credibility.
11 2 29 307 With its enormous natural gas reserves, Turkmenistan is central to European efforts to diversify gas supplies away from Russia.
11 2 30 308 Berdymukhamedov has voiced support for giving the West more access to Turkmen gas.
11 3 1 309 Voters in Turkmenistan <MENTION CHAIN="1">cast</MENTION> ballots Sunday in a parliamentary election <MENTION CHAIN="4">hailed</MENTION> by the government as an exercise in democracy but <MENTION CHAIN="2">dismissed</MENTION> by critics as a sham.
11 3 2 310 The election of a 125-seat national legislature is the first parliamentary vote in the natural-gas rich Central Asian nation since the death of longtime autocrat Saparmurat Niyazov two years ago.
11 3 3 311 His successor, Gurbanguli Berdymukhamedov, says the election is a key step in the development of democracy.
11 3 4 312 But while the seats are contested, only one political party is legally registered in Turkmenistan, and its opponents have no foothold in politics.
11 3 5 313 The U.S. and Europe are courting Turkmenistan as they seek to diversify energy sources and were watching the vote for signs of change.
11 4 1 314 The people of Turkmenistan have <MENTION CHAIN="1">voted</MENTION> in the first parliamentary election held after the <MENTION CHAIN="3">adoption</MENTION> of a new constitution earlier this year.
11 4 2 315 The Central Election Commission said that turnout was almost 90%.
11 4 3 316 It was the first poll to be held under President Kurbanguly Berdymukhamedov, who has promised to end the Central Asian nation's international isolation.
11 4 4 317 The authorities say the vote is an important democratic step, but critics question the validity of the process.
11 4 5 318 Almost all of the 288 candidates running for 125 seats in the parliament came either from Turkmenistan's sole political party, the Democratic Party, or state-affiliated organisations.
11 4 6 319 All candidates were funded by the state as alternative funding was banned.
11 4 7 320 Ethnic minorities, such as the sizeable Uzbek community, were not permitted to nominate their own candidates.
11 4 8 321 International observers
11 4 9 322 There was no shortage of voters in the parliamentary elections in Turkmenistan, the former Soviet republic which borders the Caspian Sea.
11 4 10 323 According to the country's Central Election Commission the turnout was extremely high.
11 4 11 324 Almost all of the 2.5 million people eligible cast their votes, reports said.
11 4 12 325 State media proudly reported that Turkmen citizens living abroad were able to vote for the first time at Turkmen embassies and consulates.
11 4 13 326 Officials are keen to demonstrate that these elections are part of Turkmenistan's process of democratisation.
11 4 14 327 International observers from the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe were invited to monitor the poll.
11 4 15 328 They are not expected to give any formal assessment of the election proceedings.
11 4 16 329 Previously, Turkmenistan had a People's Council whose 2,507 members had to be approved by the country's late ruler, Saparmurat Niyazov, who died in 2006 after 21 years in power.
11 4 17 330 The new leader, Mr Berdymukhamedov, a former dentist, has introduced a number of measures to modernise the gas-rich nation, after years of isolation under his predecessor.
11 4 18 331 Abolishing the People's Council and reinstating the country's parliament was one of them.
11 4 19 332 However the country remains largely closed to the outside world.
11 5 1 333 Voters in reclusive Turkmenistan <MENTION CHAIN="1">elect</MENTION> a parliament Sunday in balloting <MENTION CHAIN="4">heralded</MENTION> by authorities in the natural gas-rich nation as a key step toward democratic standards but <MENTION CHAIN="2">dismissed</MENTION> by critics as a sham.
11 5 2 334 The election comes two years after the death of idiosyncratic dictator Saparmurat Niyazov, which kindled hopes here and in the West that the Central Asian country would gradually roll back its oppressive political regime and introduce greater freedoms.
11 5 3 335 Niyazov's successor, President Gurbanguli Berdymukhamedov, has revoked some of his more draconian decrees and vowed to pursue political reform.
11 5 4 336 But most of the parliamentary candidates are from the only permitted political party, and exiled opposition activists say the president has failed to live up to his promises.
11 5 5 337 ``Beyond all the pompous declarations, there will be no real change,'' Tadzhigul Begmedova, director of the Turkmenistan Helsinki Foundation for Human Rights, said by telephone from Varna, Bulgaria.
11 5 6 338 ``The hopes many people had that a new president would open up Turkmen society have been shattered.''
11 5 7 339 On the surface, Turkmenistan's political landscape is changing.
11 5 8 340 In September, the rubber-stamp People's Council - a 2,507-member assembly of presidential appointees, town elders and others - voted to abolish itself and cede most of its powers to an expanded parliament.
11 5 9 341 But out of the 288 candidates running for the 125 seats Sunday, more than half are members of the pro-presidential Democratic Party of Turkmenistan - a political force created out of the ashes of the Soviet-era Turkmen Communist Party.
11 5 10 342 Non-party candidates have been drawn from state-controlled women's and veterans' organizations, trade unions and a youth group.
11 5 11 343 The only non-party candidate in the capital, Ashgabat, avidly supports Berdymukhamedov - undermining official claims the polls will offer a wide choice.
11 5 12 344 ``I will devote all my strengths to the honest and righteous support of our esteemed president's domestic and foreign policy,'' the candidate, regional bureaucrat Resulberdy Mammedov, said in a campaign statement.
11 5 13 345 Niyazov isolated Turkmenistan from the international community and forged a pervasive personality cult.
11 5 14 346 He called himself Turkmenbashi, or father of all Turkmens, renamed months after himself and his mother, and made his self-penned spiritual tome mandatory reading for students and state employees.
11 5 15 347 With Berdymukhamedov decreasing the country's isolation, government opponents claim the election is aimed to appease Western countries that are eager to win access to its vast natural-gas reserves but wary of its record on democracy and human rights.
11 5 16 348 The U.S. and European Union are seeking to lessen Russia's control over exports of Turkmen gas.
11 5 17 349 ``This whole spectacle has been arranged for the international community, to show that Turkmenistan is following the path of democratization,'' said Begmedova.
11 5 18 350 While officials have extolled the vote as an exercise in democracy, there has been little campaigning and little coverage on state-run television, in contrast with the February 2007 presidential election that confirmed Berdymukhamedov's role as head of state.
11 5 19 351 ``There are very few billboards around the city.
11 5 20 352 With just four days to go before the election, I still don't know who I'm supposed to vote for,'' said Maral, 45, an Ashgabat resident who declined to give her surname for fear of official intimidation.
