19 12 10 1293 The youths smashed windows newly replaced after four days of the worst riots Greece has seen in decades.
19 12 11 1294 More than 10,000 people had been marching through central Athens to protest the conservative Government's economic policies in a general strike that has shut down schools, public services and hospitals and grounded flights.
19 12 12 1295 Although the strike and demonstrations had been scheduled long before the riots broke out, they have taken on the added form of protest against the Government's handling of the riots.
19 13 1 1296 A WEEK ago, the name Alexis Grigoropoulos was just a name, an ordinary person leading an ordinary life in Athens, struggling to survive in the city.
19 13 2 1297 Alexis did not have an opportunity to live his life to the full because on Saturday December 6 he was gunned down by a police officer from the unruly 'Zita' wing of the police force.
19 13 3 1298 The death of the 15 year old sparked off uprisings throughout the whole of Greece, and for several days and nights, parts of central Athens looked like a war zone.
19 13 4 1299 The government, eager to quell the unrest, called for unity and chose to target the anarcho-koukoulofori - the so-called ``hoodies''.
19 13 5 1300 Just like with the fires in the summer of 2006, Prime Minister Kostas Karamanlis had lost control;
19 13 6 1301 it felt as if the country was stateless.
19 13 7 1302 Ignoring the indignation felt throughout Greece on the killing of the innocent teenager, within two days one sensed an emerging cover-up.
19 13 8 1303 Rumours circulated that the Zita policeman did not fire directly.
19 13 9 1304 By Tuesday, Alexis was buried.
19 13 10 1305 On Wednesday two Zita officers Epaminondas Korkoneas and Vassilios Saraliotis found themselves in court.
19 13 11 1306 Their lawyer claimed the bullet was a ricochet and that two or three shots had been fired in the air.
19 13 12 1307 In many ways this is an excuse, a fable, because bullets cannot bounce from the sky and then land accidentally around the region of an innocent person's heart!
19 13 13 1308 The state should have also conducted a much deeper probe into the death of the teenager, with a full independent ballistic and post-mortem inquiry.
19 13 14 1309 Alexis Grigoropoulos is not just a name;
19 13 15 1310 he has become a symbol of resistance, a person who died way too young in a world that was far too harsh.
19 13 16 1311 He is also not alone.
19 13 17 1312 A long list of over 100 people has been accumulated since 1980;
19 13 18 1313 all victims of the police, making the recent case just the tip of the iceberg.
19 13 19 1314 What is most worrying though is if the court accepts the ricochet theory it is likely Kornoneas and his accomplice Saraliotis will not be convicted.
19 13 20 1315 And if that happens.
19 13 21 1316 Why do people riot?
19 13 22 1317 My infamous sociology professor asked a seminar room full of students nearly 30 years ago.
19 13 23 1318 In the comfort of a room brimming full with hundreds of books stacked on shelves, a desk and the floor I initially thought the question was an exercise in scholastic nihilism.
19 13 24 1319 So many books, I wondered out loud, and no answers.
19 13 25 1320 Maybe it was my encounters with reality a week earlier in Kirkby, Liverpool, where caught in the middle of a full scale riot I had witnessed something that maybe he had not.
19 13 26 1321 Trying to elaborate on this in a reflective way, the professor dismissed my answer as way too subjective.
19 13 27 1322 After which point I turned off for the rest of the lecture and he bleated on about Durkheim and Weber some more.
19 13 28 1323 Hopefully professors nowadays are more sensitive and may be they will see rioting in a more spherical sense.
19 13 29 1324 There is always a root cause, an incident that sparks things off.
19 13 30 1325 There are also much deeper causes, economic; political which are manifest through injustices such as high unemployment, racism and state authoritarianism.
19 13 31 1326 The deepest cause of all, however, is politicians who abuse their powers in the name of ideology in ways that are dogmatic and plainly ignorant.
19 13 32 1327 Margaret Thatcher, then PM in Britain had similar trade mark tendencies as the current Greek government.
19 13 33 1328 The Zita crackpot troops in the Greek police force resemble the then British Special Patrol Group, who were responsible for the murder of many civilians.
19 13 34 1329 Special elite forces of any kind in any police force can step beyond their line of duty, becoming detrimental to the public's perception of policing in society.
19 13 35 1330 One difference, however, with Britain is the level of corruption rife in Greek politics.
19 13 36 1331 For example, the Interior Minister, Prokopis Pavlopoulos, has appointed 3, 000 people to the elite Zita force since his appointment.
19 13 37 1332 Most of these appointments have a certain political leaning.
19 13 38 1333 Furthermore The Z-force does not go through the same training in the Police Academy making them a law unto themselves.
19 13 39 1334 Just two days after the death of Alexis Grigoroplous, a Zedder fired 15 shots into the air in a confrontation with a small group of 12-13 year olds who were rioting in Mesoghieon Avenue in central Athens.
19 13 40 1335 Given this behaviour it is a miracle that no one else has died, civilian or police.
19 13 41 1336 Instead of trying to control the situation through yet more draconian measures, Karamanlis should conduct a complete independent inquiry, with proper objective and scientific evidence.
19 13 42 1337 Only than can justice be done and only then will any semblance of faith in the Greek police force be restored.
19 13 43 1338 If he opts for the same old approach of managing a tragic situation through bad public relations, not only are his political days numbered but Greece will be in a state of perpetual unrest.
19 14 1 1339 Fury at report clearing Greek police over death of schoolboy
19 14 2 1340 Greeks have reacted with fury to an official report which concluded a schoolboy whose death triggered riots across the country was killed by an accidental ricochet.
19 14 3 1341 The finding came as a nationwide strike paralysed Greece, with banks, schools and shops closed, flights in and out of the country halted and even the Parthenon barred to tourists.
19 14 4 1342 The fatal <MENTION CHAIN="8">shooting</MENTION> of Alexis Grigoropoulos, 15, on Saturday <MENTION CHAIN="5">sparked</MENTION> five days of <MENTION CHAIN="3">riots</MENTION> and <MENTION CHAIN="2">demonstrations</MENTION> across Greece after witnesses claimed that the police officer deliberately took <MENTION CHAIN="12">aim</MENTION> at the teenager.
19 14 5 1343 But the lawyer acting for the officer, who has been charged with murder, said that initial results from a post-mortem showed that the boy was accidentally hit by a ricochet.
19 14 6 1344 Forensic experts said the bullet was ``a bit deformed'', suggesting that it had bounced off a hard surface before hitting Grigoropoulos in the chest.
19 14 7 1345 Lawyer Alexis Kougias said: `` This tragedy is the result ... of an act by the policeman to fire into the air.
19 14 8 1346 The bullet ricocheted, we have an entry wound from above.
19 14 9 1347 It proves irrefutably that it was a ricochet.''
19 14 10 1348 But the tens of thousands of students who have taken to the streets of a dozen Greek cities this week have pointed out similarities to the case of another 15-year-old, Michalis Kaltezas, who was killed by an officer during a demonstration in Athens in 1985.
19 14 11 1349 The officer accused of shooting him in the back of the head was initially convicted of murder but was later found innocent after an appeal.
19 14 12 1350 Anthony Livanios, a political analyst and pollster, said: ``People will not buy it and there's a possibility that it will make things worse.
19 14 13 1351 It will be met with cynicism.
19 14 14 1352 Even if it's true, which it might be, it will be seen as a cover-up.''
19 14 15 1353 Protesters threw two petrol bombs at Athens's main courthouse where the officer and his partner were questioned by a magistrate.
19 14 16 1354 They also attacked a television crew's truck, injuring at least two people.
19 14 17 1355 In Athens' main Constitution Square, where 10,000 gathered for an anti-government demonstration, riot police guarding parliament fired tear gas at demonstrators who attacked them with petrol bombs and cobblestones.
