19 3 9 1404 The Focus poll of 1,000 people for Real News gave a 3.1 percent margin of error.
19 3 10 1405 Violence has wracked Greece every day since the death of 15-year-old Alexandros Grigoropoulos, spreading quickly from Athens to more than a dozen other cities and leaving at least 70 people injured.
19 3 11 1406 Hundreds of stores have been smashed and looted, and more than 200 people arrested.
19 3 12 1407 Late Saturday and early Sunday, youths in Athens attacked a police station, stores and banks and fought running battles with police, as candlelit vigils were held to mark a week since the shooting.
19 3 13 1408 A new candlelit vigil is planned for Sunday evening at the site of the shooting.
19 3 14 1409 A separate protest is scheduled in western Athens.
19 3 15 1410 While most of the protesters have been peaceful, the tone of the demonstrations has been set by a violent fringe.
19 3 16 1411 And more young people have been willing to join those fringe elements than in the past.
19 3 17 1412 ``In the end, the violence that we use is minimal in comparison to the violence the system uses, like the banks,'' said 32-year-old protester Paris Kyriakides.
19 3 18 1413 ``Speaking as an anarchist, we want to create those social conditions that will generate more uprisings and to get more people out in the streets to demand their rights.''
19 3 19 1414 In a poll released Sunday, some 62 percent of respondents said the reactions to the shooting were inexcusable, compared with 35 percent who believed the violence was justified.
19 3 20 1415 The poll of 1,000 people gave no margin of error.
19 3 21 1416 According to another poll, Greeks see more in the violence than a simple reaction to the shooting.
19 3 22 1417 Asked whether the riots were a social uprising, 60 percent responded yes.
19 3 23 1418 Some 64 percent considered police were unprepared for the violence.
19 3 24 1419 The poll of 520 people published in the Kathimerini newspaper gave a 4.5 percent margin of error.
