19 4 13 1432 Then something else stirred.
19 4 14 1433 A coming-of-age generation from Thessaloniki to Athens rose up to attack dozens of police stations, occupy university campuses and prompt the closing of the international airport.
19 4 15 1434 Some of their demands are immediate:
19 4 16 1435 They want police banned from carrying guns.
19 4 17 1436 Others are less defined:
19 4 18 1437 They are looking for government to change.
19 4 19 1438 The center-right government of Costas Karamanlis, increasingly unpopular amid mounting economic problems, didn't anticipate or understand how the anger had spiraled.
19 4 20 1439 The youth were suddenly lashing out at all that ails Greece: a weak government, an economy that remains one of the poorest of the European Union and their own bleak job prospects.
19 4 21 1440 They looted businesses, pelted police with stones and ran amok near government banks, offices and university campuses with Molotov cocktails.
19 4 22 1441 About 100 people have been injured.
19 4 23 1442 Property damage is an estimated $2 million.
19 4 24 1443 Talk of what happened in Athens and Thessaloniki has spread to Italy and Spain, which have had protests of their own.
19 4 25 1444 Few of the dozen people interviewed in Athens said they had a permanent job or a job that guaranteed a pension.
19 4 26 1445 Many older spectators said they are sympathetic - even if they didn't like the ruin left behind.
19 4 27 1446 ``I feel sorry for the young, `` said 40-year-old Tsikala Stephania, a public sector worker.
19 4 28 1447 ``They don't see much of a future, and they have to show their wrath in some way.''
19 5 1 1448 Athens vigil ends in violence
