2 7 1 1738 The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences <MENTION CHAIN="4">announced</MENTION> Friday that Hugh Jackman will be the <MENTION CHAIN="2">host</MENTION> of the 81st annual Oscars on Feb. 22 at the Kodak Theatre.
2 7 2 1739 The lanky Australian, who was recently named People magazine's Sexiest Man Alive, is best known for playing Wolverine in the ``X-Men'' franchise, including the upcoming ``X-Men Origins: Wolverine,'' and for his romantic adventure roles in the current period drama ``Australia'' and as a vampire hunter in ``Van Helsing.''
2 7 3 1740 Not exactly the wild and crazy comedy type that has been hosting the Oscars for the last 20 years, a list that includes names such as Billy Crystal, David Letterman, Steve Martin, Whoopi Goldberg, Jon Stewart and Ellen DeGeneres.
2 7 4 1741 In addition to looking great in a tux, the 40-year-old Jackman has TV hosting experience.
2 7 5 1742 He emceed both the 2004 and 2005 Tony Awards, and won an Emmy Award for his first go at hosting that award show.
2 7 6 1743 ``He is so sparkling and personable, and he delivers,`` said academy President Sid Ganis.
2 7 7 1744 ``I saw him recently at a Motion Picture Home event on the Sony lot.
2 7 8 1745 He is charming and pleasant.
2 7 9 1746 The other thing is:
2 7 10 1747 He loves [being the host].
2 7 11 1748 He loves the patter.
2 7 12 1749 He likes to wink his eye at an audience and have fun.''
2 7 13 1750 While it's been more than two decades since a non-comedian was one of the Academy Award hosts, the Jackman announcement is hardly unprecedented.
2 7 14 1751 Numerous actors, directors and even producers have served as master of ceremonies.
2 7 15 1752 Douglas Fairbanks, Laurence Olivier, James Stewart, Ingrid Bergman, Jane Fonda, Alan Alda, Claudette Colbert, Fredric March, Agnes Moorhead, Thelma Ritter, Fred Astaire and Charlton Heston have all played host on Oscar night.
2 7 16 1753 ``We're sort of going back to the pre-Bob Hope days a little bit,'' said Oscar producer Laurence Mark, explaining that the decision to return to an actor as host was influenced by a desire to change what he called the ``late-night talk-show'' feel of past programs.
2 7 17 1754 ``We wanted to take the show to another form,'' Mark said.
2 7 18 1755 ``Hugh seemed to be the perfect person.
2 7 19 1756 The lovely thing about the show is it is a TV show set in a theater about the movies, so the fact that he is a movie star... he's also an extraordinary stage presence and he does actually have an Emmy Award for hosting the Tonys.
2 7 20 1757 He fits all three bills.''
2 7 21 1758 ``Thirty years ago when I was in Sydney watching Johnny Carson host the Oscars with my family, I never imagined that I'd one day have the chance to be up on that stage myself,'' Jackman said in a statement.
2 7 22 1759 The academy is hoping that Jackman's international appeal will help bring more viewers to the annual event that is telecast on ABC.
2 7 23 1760 Ratings for the Oscar telecast have declined sharply in recent years, especially among young-adult audiences.
2 7 24 1761 The 2008 telecast delivered 32 million total viewers, a 24% drop compared with the previous year's ceremony, according to figures from Nielsen Media Research.
2 7 25 1762 The most-watched Academy Awards in recent years was in 1998, when ``Titanic'' won best picture.
2 7 26 1763 A total of 55.3 million people tuned in to watch who took home the golden statuettes.
