28 1 1 2519 Lawman's Unwavering Compass Led Him to White House Showdown
28 1 2 2520 W. Mark Felt Sr., the associate director of the FBI during the Watergate <MENTION CHAIN="2">scandal</MENTION> who, better known as ``Deep Throat,'' became the most famous anonymous source in American history, <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> yesterday.
28 1 3 2521 Felt <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> at 12:45 p.m. at his home in Santa Rosa, Calif.
28 1 4 2522 On Tuesday, Oct. 10, 1972, Washington awoke to this startling news:
28 1 5 2523 ``FBI agents have established that the Watergate bugging incident stemmed from a massive campaign of political spying and sabotage conducted on behalf of President Nixon's reelection and directed by officials of the White House and the Committee for the Re-election of the President,'' The Washington Post reported.
28 1 6 2524 Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein wrote that story, but it would not have been possible, they would later tell the world, without the clandestine help of the most famous unnamed source in history, W. Mark Felt -- the man they called ``Deep Throat.''
28 1 7 2525 He was the associate director of the FBI, and he guided the reporters, all along insisting that Watergate was not an isolated incident but part of a wider conspiracy designed to destroy Democratic presidential candidates who might run against Nixon.
28 1 8 2526 Instead, the Watergate scandal subsequently destroyed the Nixon presidency.
28 1 9 2527 Facing impeachment, Nixon resigned the presidency in disgrace less than two years after that day in October when, one of his key lawyers would later say, it was apparent that ``in a general way and with the help of Deep Throat, (Woodward and Bernstein) figured out Watergate.''
28 1 10 2528 Felt died Thursday at his home in Santa Rosa, Calif.
28 1 11 2529 He was 95.
28 1 12 2530 As the second-ranking official in the FBI, Felt possessed authoritative knowledge of what came to be known as the Watergate conspiracy.
28 1 13 2531 Felt had personally witnessed the Nixon administration's attempt to subvert the bureau's investigation into the complex of crimes and coverups that began unraveling with a 1972 burglary of the Democratic National Committee's headquarters at the Watergate complex in Northwest Washington.
28 1 14 2532 ``He helped stiffen the spine of The Washington Post, which went out on a limb more than any other publication did, and broke stories that other outlets shunned,'' said Mark Feldstein, a George Washington University faculty member who is writing a book on Nixon and the media.
28 1 15 2533 ``Had Woodward not run with it, Felt had a network of connections in Washington, (other reporters) he was talking to ... but no one knew of his connection to Woodward.''
28 1 16 2534 Felt, a dashing figure with a full head of silver hair and a reputation as a taskmaster, adamantly denied over the years that he was Deep Throat, even though Nixon suspected him almost from the start.
28 1 17 2535 Nixon ordered interim FBI director L. Patrick Gray to fire Felt five times.
28 1 18 2536 But Gray, convinced by Felt's denials, never did.
28 1 19 2537 A master of bureaucratic infighting and misdirection, Felt seized upon a Post story that had not used him as a source.
28 1 20 2538 In a bold stroke, he denounced it in an internal memo and ordered an investigation into the leak.
28 1 21 2539 ``Expedite,'' he commanded.
28 1 22 2540 The next day, in a notation on another memo that passed across his desk, he pointed to a prosecutor as the source of the leak.
28 1 23 2541 ``I was impressed.
28 1 24 2542 My guy knew his stuff,'' Woodward wrote in ``Secret Man: The Story of Watergate's Deep Throat'' (2006).
28 1 25 2543 ``The memo was an effective cover for him, the very best counterintelligence tradecraft.
28 1 26 2544 Not only had he initiated the leak inquiry, but Felt appeared to have discovered the leaker.''
28 1 27 2545 Felt had insisted on remaining completely anonymous, or on ``deep background.''
28 1 28 2546 A Post editor dubbed him ``Deep Throat,'' a bit of wordplay based on the title of a pornographic movie of the time.
28 1 29 2547 The source's existence, but not his identity, became known in Woodward and Bernstein's 1974 book, ``All the President's Men,'' and in the subsequent movie version, in which actor Hal Holbrook played the charismatic but shadowy source.
28 1 30 2548 It wasn't until May 30, 2005, that Felt's family revealed his identity in an article for Vanity Fair magazine.
28 1 31 2549 The story, written by San Francisco lawyer John D. O'Connor, did not make clear why Felt, who was suffering from dementia, admitted his role after more than 30 years. 
28 1 32 2550 Woodward confirmed the revelation, and the secret was finally out.
28 10 1 2551 Mark Felt, who was known as Watergate <MENTION CHAIN="2">scandal</MENTION> informant 'Deep Throat,' <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> on Friday.
28 10 2 2552 He was 95.
28 10 3 2553 Felt worked as the associate director of the FBI in the 1970s and is one of the most famous anonymous sources for the press in American history.
28 10 4 2554 His daughter Joan Felt said her father ate a big breakfast before saying he was tired, and went to sleep, she told the Washington Post.
28 10 5 2555 He died at 12:45 p.m. on Thursday at his home in Santa Rosa, California, the Post stated.
28 10 6 2556 ``He slipped away,'' she said.
28 10 7 2557 Felt blew the whistle on a corrupt administration trying to cover up attempts to sabotage opponents.
28 10 8 2558 He secretly guided Washington Post reporter Bob Woodward and his colleague Carl Bernstein who pursued the story of the 1972 break-in of the Democratic National Committee's headquarters at the Watergate office buildings.
28 10 9 2559 That ultimately led to the resignation of President Richard M. Nixon.
28 10 10 2560 Felt insisted on remaining completely anonymous until May 30, 2005 when Felt's family revealed his identity in an article for Vanity Fair magazine.
28 11 1 2561 Mark Felt, 'Deep Throat' of Watergate, dead at 95
28 11 2 2562 W. Mark Felt, who <MENTION CHAIN="11">leaked</MENTION> information to reporters under the moniker, ``Deep Throat,'' about the Watergate break-in, <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> Thursday at the age of 95, sources told CNN.
28 11 3 2563 Mark Felt, known as ``Deep Throat,'' divulged information to reporters about the Watergate break-in.
28 11 4 2564 Rob Jones, Felt's grandson, said his grandfather <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> at his home in Santa Rosa, California.
28 11 5 2565 According to published reports, Felt <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> of congestive heart failure.
28 11 6 2566 Felt admitted in a 2005 Vanity Fair article he was the Washington Post's source for many of its 400 stories on the Watergate affair during the early nineteen seventies.
28 11 7 2567 The Watergate break-in eventually led to the 1974 resignation of President Richard Nixon.
28 11 8 2568 ``I'm proud of everything that Deep Throat did,'' Felt, 92, told CNN's ``Larry King Live'' in 2006, his first public interview on the subject.
28 11 9 2569 Felt's entanglement with history occurred in 1972 after the bungled break-in at the Democratic National Party offices in the Watergate hotel.
28 11 10 2570 Felt, an associate director at the FBI, said he was unhappy with the way the administration meddled with the investigation into the break-in, which led him to divulge information to the newspaper.
28 11 11 2571 Video Watch how Felt played a pivotal role in presidential history
28 11 12 2572 Carl Bernstein and Bob Woodward, then-rookie reporters with the Washington Post, did stories about the break-in and subsequent cover-up.
28 11 13 2573 Both men credited Felt for helping them, but Bernstein said Felt was a tough interview.
28 11 14 2574 ``He didn't leak.
28 11 15 2575 He had to really be squeezed,'' Bernstein said in a 2006 interview.
28 11 16 2576 ``He confirmed mostly what we had gotten elsewhere.
28 11 17 2577 He didn't want to volunteer a lot of information, yet his role was essential in giving us a solidity and a knowledge that what we were reporting was right.''
28 12 1 2578 Mark Felt, 'Deep Throat' in Watergate reports, dies
28 12 2 2579 Former FBI official had storied role in Washington Post investigation that brought down Nixon
28 12 3 2580 W. Mark Felt, the former FBI official who <MENTION CHAIN="6">ended</MENTION> one of the United States' most intriguing political mysteries when he <MENTION CHAIN="6">identified</MENTION> himself as ``Deep Throat'' -- the nickname for the anonymous source who <MENTION CHAIN="3">helped</MENTION> guide The Washington Post's Pulitzer Prize-winning <MENTION CHAIN="8">investigation</MENTION> into the Watergate <MENTION CHAIN="2">scandal</MENTION> -- has <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION>.
28 12 4 2581 He was 95.
28 12 5 2582 A controversial figure who was later <MENTION CHAIN="12">convicted</MENTION> of <MENTION CHAIN="13">authorizing</MENTION> illegal activities in pursuit of members of the radical Weather Underground, Felt <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> of heart failure Thursday at his home in Santa Rosa, Calif., his grandson Rob Jones said.
28 12 6 2583 Felt was deputy associate director of the FBI in 1972 when he began supplying information to Bob Woodward, who with Carl Bernstein made up The Post's investigative duo who doggedly pursued the story of the Watergate break-in and a conspiracy that led directly to President Richard M. Nixon, who ultimately resigned.
28 12 7 2584 The reporters continued to keep Felt's name a secret, but in 2005, at the age of 91, Felt told Vanity Fair magazine, ``I'm the guy they used to call Deep Throat.''
28 12 8 2585 His disclosure ended a mystery that had intrigued Washington insiders and journalists for three decades and provided the grist for many hotly debated newspaper and magazine articles.
28 12 9 2586 While Felt's name was raised as a suspect on several occasions, he always managed to deflect attention, usually by saying that if had been Deep Throat he would have done a better job of exposing the wrongdoings at the White House.
28 12 10 2587 His disclosure in a Vanity Fair article by his family's lawyer, John D. O'Connor, provoked a national debate:
28 12 11 2588 Was he a hero who should be lauded for sparing the country the strain of further high crimes and misdemeanors by the Nixon White House?
28 12 12 2589 Or was he a traitor who betrayed not only his president but his oath of office by disclosing grand jury information and the contents of FBI files?
28 12 13 2590 For the most part, reaction split along political lines.
28 12 14 2591 ``There's nothing heroic about breaking faith with your people,'' said commentator Patrick J. Buchanan, a former Nixon speechwriter.
28 12 15 2592 Felt ``disgraced himself and dishonored everything an FBI agent should stand for.''
28 12 16 2593 But Richard Ben-Veniste, a key lawyer in the Watergate prosecution team, said Felt's role showed that ``the importance of whistle-blowers shouldn't be underestimated, particularly when there are excesses by the executive branch of government -- which in this case went all the way to the executive office.''
28 12 17 2594 Felt's moment in history began to unfold shortly after five men in business suits were arrested at the Watergate complex in Washington on June 17, 1972, after breaking into the offices of the Democratic National Committee.
28 12 18 2595 Nixon press secretary Ron Ziegler dismissed the incident as ``a third-rate burglary,'' but details gradually tumbled out tying the burglars to the president's re-election campaign.
28 12 19 2596 Misdeeds in the White House were uncovered, hearings were conducted in the House of Representatives and Senate, and for the first time in American history a president was forced to resign.
28 12 20 2597 The relationship that defined a generation in journalism began about 1970 when Woodward was a Navy lieutenant assigned to the Pentagon as a watch officer.
28 12 21 2598 In his book, ``The Secret Man: The Story of Watergate's Deep Throat,'' published after the Vanity Fair article appeared, Woodward wrote that he met Felt when he delivered a package of documents to the White House and struck up a conversation with him in a waiting room.
28 12 22 2599 From that initial meeting, Woodward cultivated a friendship that would pay off handsomely after he entered journalism.
28 12 23 2600 Felt began to provide tips to Woodward when he was a cub reporter at the Montgomery County Sentinel, a suburban Maryland newspaper, and later at The Post, where he was tipped by Felt on stories about the investigation of the 1972 shooting of George C. Wallace, the Alabama governor then running for president.
28 12 24 2601 When Woodward was assigned to the Watergate break-in, he again pressed Felt for help.
28 12 25 2602 His request came during a crucial moment in the FBI's history:
28 12 26 2603 Felt's mentor, the legendary founding director J. Edgar Hoover, had died the month before the break-in, and Assistant Attorney General L. Patrick Gray III had been named acting director.
28 12 27 2604 Felt feared -- and his suspicions were later proven right -- that Gray was too close to the Nixon administration to conduct an uncompromised investigation.
28 12 28 2605 Felt agreed to help Woodward but only on ``deep background,'' a term meaning that ``the information could be used,'' Woodward wrote, ``but no source of any kind would be identified in the newspaper.''
28 12 29 2606 Felt insisted on using covert rules he had learned while working in the FBI's espionage section during World War II.
28 12 30 2607 If Woodward needed to talk to Felt, he would move a flower pot with a red cloth flag in it to the front of his apartment balcony.
28 12 31 2608 If Felt needed to talk to the reporter -- to correct something The Post had written or to convey other information -- he would circle page 20 in Woodward's home-delivered copy of The New York Times and draw clock hands on the page to indicate the time of the meeting.
28 12 32 2609 He resisted telephone contact in favor of clandestine 2 a.m. encounters at an underground parking garage in Rosslyn, Virginia.
28 12 33 2610 The two met from June 19, 1972 -- two days after the break-in -- to November 1973, five months after Felt left the FBI.
28 12 34 2611 Within the paper, only Woodward and Bernstein knew the identity of Deep Throat, a name borrowed from a notorious pornographic movie of the era.
28 12 35 2612 But Felt dealt only with Woodward, and Bernstein did not meet him until 2008.
28 12 36 2613 When Nixon left office on Aug. 9, 1974, the two reporters shared the secret with Post Editor Benjamin C. Bradlee, who until then had only known that the source was a high Justice Department official.
28 12 37 2614 Nixon, according to Woodward, had suspected Felt of being the confidential source and assumed him to be part of a Jewish cabal out to get him.
28 12 38 2615 According to Vanity Fair, Felt had no religious affiliation.
