28 2 3 2633 In its report on Felt's death, the New York Times called him ``the most famous anonymous source in American history.''
28 2 4 2634 Felt, the No. 2 official at the FBI when the Watergate case broke, kept his role in the story a secret for 30 years. 
28 2 5 2635 Only in 2005, at age 91, was his part made public in an article in Vanity Fair magazine written by Felt's family lawyer.
28 2 6 2636 ``I'm the guy they used to call Deep Throat,'' Felt told attorney John O'Connor.
28 2 7 2637 For years, people had speculated and argued about the identity of ``Deep Throat,'' whose name was derived from the title of a popular pornographic movie.
28 2 8 2638 Vanity Fair scooped Woodward and Bernstein, who had promised not to reveal the name of the star source of their 1974 stories until after his death.
28 2 9 2639 But within a day of Felt's unveiling, Woodward wrote of his relationship with Felt.
28 2 10 2640 Woodward said he turned to Felt after he and Bernstein wrote about the break-in at the offices of the Democratic National Committee at the Watergate complex in Washington.
28 3 1 2641 Mark Felt, Watergate's `Deep Throat,' dies at 95
28 3 2 2642 W. Mark Felt, the former FBI second-in-command who <MENTION CHAIN="6">revealed</MENTION> himself as ``Deep Throat'' 30 years after he <MENTION CHAIN="3">tipped</MENTION> off reporters to the Watergate <MENTION CHAIN="2">scandal</MENTION> that <MENTION CHAIN="5">toppled</MENTION> a president, has <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION>.
28 3 3 2643 He was 95.
28 3 4 2644 Felt <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> Thursday in Santa Rosa after suffering from congestive heart failure for several months, said family friend John D. O'Connor, who <MENTION CHAIN="7">wrote</MENTION> the 2005 Vanity Fair article <MENTION CHAIN="6">uncovering</MENTION> Felt's secret.
28 3 5 2645 The shadowy central figure in the one of the most gripping political dramas of the 20th century, Felt insisted his alter ego be kept secret when he leaked damaging information about President Richard Nixon and his aides to Washington Post reporter Bob Woodward.
28 3 6 2646 While some - including Nixon and his aides - speculated that Felt was the source who connected the White House to the June 1972 break-in at the headquarters of the Democratic National Committee, he steadfastly denied the accusations until finally coming forward in May 2005.
28 3 7 2647 ``I'm the guy they used to call Deep Throat,'' Felt told O'Connor for the Vanity Fair article, creating a whirlwind of media attention.
28 3 8 2648 Weakened by a stroke, the man who had kept his secret for decades wasn't doing much talking - he merely waved to the media from the front door of his daughter's Santa Rosa home.
28 3 9 2649 Critics, including those who went to prison for the Watergate scandal, called him a traitor for betraying the commander in chief.
28 3 10 2650 Supporters hailed him as a hero for blowing the whistle on a corrupt administration trying to cover up attempts to sabotage opponents.
28 3 11 2651 Felt grappled with his place in history, arguing with his children over whether to reveal his identity or to take his secret to the grave, O'Connor said.
28 3 12 2652 He agonized about what revealing his identity would do to his reputation.
28 3 13 2653 Would he be seen as a turncoat or a man of honor?
28 3 14 2654 ``People will debate for a long time whether I did the right thing by helping Woodward,'' Felt wrote in his 2006 memoir, ``A G-Man's Life: The FBI, `Deep Throat' and the Struggle for Honor in Washington.''
28 3 15 2655 ``The bottom line is that we did get the whole truth out, and isn't that what the FBI is supposed to do?''
28 3 16 2656 Ultimately, his daughter, Joan, persuaded him to go public;
28 3 17 2657 after all, Woodward was sure to profit by revealing the secret after Felt died.
28 3 18 2658 ``We could make at least enough money to pay some bills, like the debt I've run up for the kids' education,'' she told her father, according to the Vanity Fair article.
28 3 19 2659 ``Let's do it for the family.''
28 3 20 2660 The revelation capped a Washington whodunnit that spanned more than three decades and seven presidents.
28 3 21 2661 It was the final mystery of Watergate, the subject of the best-selling book and hit movie ``All the President's Men,'' which inspired a generation of college students to pursue journalism.
28 3 22 2662 It was by chance that Felt came to play a pivotal role in the drama.
28 3 23 2663 Back in 1970, Woodward struck up a conversation with Felt while both were waiting in a White House hallway.
28 3 24 2664 Felt apparently took a liking to the young Woodward, then a Navy courier, and Woodward kept the relationship going, treating Felt as a mentor as he tried to figure out the ways of Washington.
28 3 25 2665 Later, while Woodward and partner Carl Bernstein relied on various unnamed sources in reporting on Watergate, the man their editor dubbed ``Deep Throat'' helped to keep them on track and confirm vital information.
28 3 26 2666 The Post won a Pulitzer Prize for its Watergate coverage.
28 3 27 2667 Within days of the burglary at Watergate that launched the Post's investigative series, Woodward phoned Felt.
28 3 28 2668 ``He reminded me how he disliked phone calls at the office but said that the Watergate burglary case was going to `heat up' for reasons he could not explain,'' Woodward wrote after Felt was named.
28 3 29 2669 ``He then hung up abruptly.''
28 3 30 2670 Felt helped Woodward link former CIA man Howard Hunt to the break-in.
28 3 31 2671 He said the reporter could accurately write that Hunt, whose name was found in the address book of one of the burglars, was a suspect.
28 3 32 2672 But Felt told him off the record, insisting that their relationship and Felt's identity remain secret.
28 3 33 2673 Worried that phones were being tapped, Felt arranged clandestine meetings worthy of a spy novel.
28 3 34 2674 Woodward would move a flower pot with a red flag on his balcony if he needed to meet Felt.
28 3 35 2675 The G-man would scrawl a time to meet on page 20 of Woodward's copy of The New York Times and they would rendezvous in a suburban Virginia parking garage in the dead of night.
28 3 36 2676 In the movie, the enduring image of Deep Throat - a name borrowed from a 1972 porn movie - is of a testy, chain-smoking Hal Holbrook telling Woodward, played by Robert Redford, to ``follow the money.''
28 3 37 2677 In a memoir published in April 2006, Felt said he saw himself as a ``Lone Ranger'' who could help derail a White House cover-up.
28 3 38 2678 Felt wrote that he was upset by the slow pace of the FBI investigation into the Watergate break-in and believed the press could pressure the administration to cooperate.
28 3 39 2679 ``From the start, it was clear that senior administration officials were up to their necks in this mess, and that they would stop at nothing to sabotage our investigation,'' Felt wrote in his memoir.
28 3 40 2680 Some critics said Felt, a J. Edgar Hoover loyalist, was bitter at being passed over when Nixon appointed an FBI outsider and confidante, L. Patrick Gray, to lead the FBI after Hoover's death.
28 3 41 2681 Gray was later implicated in Watergate abuses.
28 3 42 2682 ``We had no idea of his motivations, and even now some of his motivations are unclear,'' Bernstein said.
28 3 43 2683 Felt wrote that he wasn't motivated by anger.
28 3 44 2684 ``It is true that I would have welcomed an appointment as FBI director when Hoover died.
28 3 45 2685 It is not true that I was jealous of Gray,'' he wrote.
28 3 46 2686 Felt was born in Twin Falls, Idaho, and worked for an Idaho senator during graduate school.
28 3 47 2687 After law school at George Washington University he spent a year at the Federal Trade Commission.
28 3 48 2688 Felt joined the FBI in 1942 and worked as a Nazi hunter during World War II.
28 3 49 2689 Ironically, while providing crucial information to the Post, Felt also was assigned to ferret out the newspaper's source.
28 3 50 2690 The investigation never went anywhere, but plenty of people, including those in the White House at the time, guessed that Felt, who was leading the investigation into Watergate, may have been acting as a double agent.
28 3 51 2691 The Watergate tapes captured White House chief of staff H.R. Haldeman telling Nixon that Felt was the source, but they were afraid to stop him.
28 3 52 2692 Nixon asks: ``Somebody in the FBI?''
28 3 53 2693 Haldeman: ``Yes, sir. Mark Felt ...
28 3 54 2694 If we move on him, he'll go out and unload everything.
28 3 55 2695 He knows everything that's to be known in the FBI.''
28 3 56 2696 Felt left the FBI in 1973 for the lecture circuit.
28 3 57 2697 Five years later he was indicted on charges of authorizing FBI break-ins at homes associated with suspected bombers from the 1960s radical group the Weather Underground.
28 3 58 2698 President Ronald Reagan pardoned Felt in 1981 while the case was on appeal - a move applauded by Nixon.
28 3 59 2699 Woodward and Bernstein said they wouldn't reveal the source's identity until he or she died, and finally confirmed Felt's role only after he came forward.
28 3 60 2700 O'Connor said Thursday his friend appeared to be at peace since the revelation.
28 3 61 2701 ``What I saw was a person that went from a divided personality that carried around this heavy secret to a completely integrated and glowing personality over these past few years once he let the secret out,'' he said.
28 3 62 2702 Felt is survived by two children, Joan Felt and Mark Felt Jr., and four grandchildren.
28 3 63 2703 His wife, Audrey Felt, died in 1984.
28 4 1 2704 Mark Felt, the most famous anonymous source in the history of journalism who was known to the world as ``Deep Throat'', <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> yesterday aged 95.
28 4 2 2705 As the associate director of the FBI, Mr Felt was outraged by the Nixon administration's attempts to block its investigation of the Watergate scandal which ultimately led to the resignation of President Richard Nixon in 1974.
28 4 3 2706 A master of counter-intelligence from his days tracking German WWII spies, he secretly helped Washington Post reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein pursue the story.
28 4 4 2707 It was thirty four years before he finally broke cover, admitting in 2006:
28 4 5 2708 ``I'm the guy they used to call Deep Throat.''
28 4 6 2709 By then, he was so crippled by a stroke and Alzheimer's disease that his memory of his role in US history had almost vanished.
28 4 7 2710 From the first day of the bungled 1972 break-in of the Democratic National Committee's headquarters in the Watergate hotel Mr Felt was at the heart of the FBI investigation.
28 4 8 2711 The agency soon learned that the Nixon administration was running an extensive spying and sabotage campaign against its political enemies.
28 4 9 2712 Under intense pressure from the White House to suppress its investigation, the FBI was starting to buckle.
28 4 10 2713 A protagonist of the famous FBI director Herbert Hoover, the Mr Felt was already embittered for being passed over as his replacement.
28 4 11 2714 When White House officials tried to block the FBI's corruption investigation, he became infuriated with what he would call their 'switchblade mentality.'
28 4 12 2715 A debonair man about town and incurable political gossip, Mr Felt was already known to Mr Woodward when he first reached out to him.
28 4 13 2716 Soon he was arranging cloak and dagger meetings with the young reporters in darkened parking garages across the Potomac River.
28 4 14 2717 The chain-smoking FBI-man provided an insight into the scale of the presidential scandal that was larger than anyone had imagined.
28 4 15 2718 ``Deep Throat'', the name given to him at the Washington Post, was a wordplay based on a well known pornographic movie and his insistence on remaining on ``deep background'' despite the sensational nature of his revelations.
28 4 16 2719 From the outset President Nixon suspected him of being the leaker and five times ordered the FBI director Patrick Gray to fire him.
28 4 17 2720 Felt's adamant denials were convincing enough and he was never sacked.
28 4 18 2721 Deep Throat continued to leak and on the assumption that he was being monitored he had elaborate procedures for contacting Mr Woodward.
28 4 19 2722 When he had information to pass on, he would arrange meetings by circling the page number on page twenty of the reporter's copy of The New York Times and then drawing the hands of a clock to signal the hour.
28 4 20 2723 If Mr Woodward wanted to see him he would simply place a red flag in a flowerpot on the balcony of his P street apartment.
28 4 21 2724 Over the course of the scandal, Deep Throat supplied crucial information for some 400 Washington Post stories.
28 4 22 2725 The reporters went on to win a Pulitzer prize, journalism's highest accolade.
28 4 23 2726 A master of the black arts of disinformation, at FBI headquarters he alighted on a newspaper story for which he was not the source and ordered an investigation to find the leaker.
28 4 24 2727 He then fingered a prosecutor as the source.
28 4 25 2728 Mr Woodward wrote in his 2006 expose, ``Secret Man: The Story of Watergate's Deep Throat'' that ``The memo was an effective cover for him, the very best counterintelligence tradecraft.
28 4 26 2729 Not only had he initiated the leak inquiry, but Felt appeared to have discovered the leaker.''
28 4 27 2730 By then Deep Throat's real identity had already been revealed in Vanity Fair magazine.
28 4 28 2731 More than 30 years after Watergate and Mr Woodward confirmed the revelation, finally letting his secret out.
28 4 29 2732 By then Mr Felt was suffering from dementia and had little or no memory of his role in history.
28 4 30 2733 Though Deep Throat was a hero to the anti Vietnam War movement and the left, Mr Felt was no liberal.
28 4 31 2734 A law and order crime-fighter, he ran the agency's ``goon squad'' to monitor agents in the field.
28 4 32 2735 He also advised Hollywood for its 1965 television series The FBI, ensuring that G-men were always shown in the most favourable light.
28 4 33 2736 Long after Watergate he was convicted of running his own so called ``black bag'' burglaries of the radical Weather Underground movement.
28 4 34 2737 He was later pardoned by President Ronald Reagan.
28 4 35 2738 In a 1979 book, he bragged about the FBI's bugging of the Civil Rights leader Martin Luther King and he vehemently opposed the hiring of women agents by the FBI.
28 5 1 2739 Deep Throat is dead.
28 5 2 2740 The <MENTION CHAIN="1">passing</MENTION> yesterday of W. Mark Felt, the man who was the infamous secret source for Washington Post reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein during their <MENTION CHAIN="8">investigation</MENTION> of the Watergate <MENTION CHAIN="2">scandal</MENTION>, <MENTION CHAIN="9">marks</MENTION> the end of a life that brought about both the good and the bad of anonymous sources in political journalism.
28 5 3 2741 Without Felt's information, the full scale of the Nixon administration's corruption would likely never have come to light, he wouldn't have resigned in disgrace, and it might have set a precedent that the president of the United States is above the law.
28 5 4 2742 Deep Throat also gave us a new archetype in popular culture: the shadowy insider in a trench coat, calling up reporters for secret meetings in parking garages to spill the dirt, often with gravely voices and cautious looks over the shoulder.
28 5 5 2743 It's been employed in entertainment ever since, from Hal Holbrook's performance as Deep Throat in All the President's Men, to Fox Mulder's informant in The X-Files, to even the Caped Crusader giving Vicki Vale the cure for the Joker's poison gas in Batman.
28 5 6 2744 But the downside of Felt's legacy is the increased willingness of modern day journalists to grant anonymity to sources at the drop of a fedora.
28 5 7 2745 I've been an avid reader of political news for ten years now and lost count of how many stories are attributed to someone, ``who declined to be named because they were not authorized to speak on the matter,'' or, ``who declined to be named for fear of angering the President.''
28 5 8 2746 It's become a lazy reporter's default setting to allow people to talk on ``deep background,'' and as a result we've slipped into a rut where accountability in government has become a rare, almost non-existent concept.
28 5 9 2747 All journalists should pore over the many obits of Felt today and think long and hard about their duty to the public the next time someone asks to go off the record.
28 6 1 2748 The former FBI second-in-command who <MENTION CHAIN="6">revealed</MENTION> himself as ``Deep Throat'' 30 years after he <MENTION CHAIN="3">tipped</MENTION> off reporters to the Watergate <MENTION CHAIN="2">scandal</MENTION> that <MENTION CHAIN="5">toppled</MENTION> a president has <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> .
28 6 2 2749 Mark Felt was 95. John D. O'Connor, a family friend who wrote the 2005 Vanity Fair article uncovering Felt's secret, says he died Thursday.
28 6 3 2750 The shadowy central figure in one of the most gripping political dramas of the 20th century, Felt insisted his alter ego be kept secret when he leaked damaging information about President Richard Nixon and his aides to The Washington Post.
28 6 4 2751 Some speculated that Felt was the source who connected the White House to the June 1972 break-in at the headquarters of the Democratic National Committee.
28 6 5 2752 He steadfastly denied the accusations until finally coming forward in May 2005.
28 6 6 2753 In the last week of November, the National Archives released more than 10,000 pages of documents from the Nixon presidency, among them were the urgings of past and present FBI agents and other interested citizens to appoint Felt, then the No. 2 FBI official, as director.
28 6 7 2754 Associates described his ``outstanding loyalty.''
28 6 8 2755 Nixon did not take the advice.
28 6 9 2756 Ultimately, Felt's devastating leaks as The Washington Post's secret Watergate source helped undermine Nixon's presidency.
28 6 10 2757 Nixon, soon to be consumed by the Watergate investigation, passed over career agents including Felt when he selected loyalist L. Patrick Gray as FBI chief after the J. Edgar Hoover's death in 1972, just weeks before the Watergate break-in.
28 6 11 2758 Gray resigned the next year because of allegations he had destroyed Watergate documents.
28 6 12 2759 Felt's supporters weighed in, with letters, telegrams and cards that have been in Nixon's White House files all these years.
28 6 13 2760 ``He has the integrity, the ability, the experience and the image to insure that our FBI will continue to deserve and maintain world esteem,'' Harold L. Child Jr., legal attache to the embassy in Japan and a 30-year FBI veteran, told Nixon in an April 1973 letter.
28 6 14 2761 Efton A. Stanfield, a former FBI special agent who was then an executive of the electrical contractors' association, asked Nixon in a telegram to turn to the career professional to replace Gray.
28 6 15 2762 ``Mr. Felt is a man of outstanding loyalty, character, reputation, habits,'' he said.
28 6 16 2763 The ``fidelity, bravery, and integrity of Mr. Felt are unquestioned.''
28 6 17 2764 Felt himself was the lead agent in a telegram sent to the White House by a group of agents asking that a highly qualified professional be nominated.
28 6 18 2765 The police chief in Kodiak, Alaska, made the case for Felt, and so did ordinary citizens.
28 6 19 2766 Writing from Brooklyn, N.Y., Viena K. Neaville told Nixon that choosing Felt would be good for him because, ``You would be spared the tremendous aggravation to which you are subjected by so many factions.''
28 6 20 2767 Nixon was spared no grief. 
28 6 21 2768 He eventually chose William Ruckelshaus, who served at FBI only briefly.
28 6 22 2769 Deep Throat's identity remained a mystery until Felt stepped forward in 2005 to acknowledge his clandestine role in bringing down Nixon.
28 6 23 2770 Bob Woodward of The Washington Post said he first spoke with Felt about Watergate two days after the break-in.
28 7 1 2771 Mark Felt, FBI official who became 'Deep Throat,' dead at 95
28 7 2 2772 W. Mark Felt, who was the No. 2 official at the FBI when he <MENTION CHAIN="3">helped</MENTION> <MENTION CHAIN="1">bring</MENTION> down President Richard M. Nixon by <MENTION CHAIN="10">resisting</MENTION> the Watergate cover-up and becoming Deep Throat, the most famous anonymous source in American history, <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> on Thursday.
28 7 3 2773 He was 95 and lived in Santa Rosa.
28 7 4 2774 His death was confirmed by Rob Jones, his grandson.
28 7 5 2775 In 2005, Felt revealed that he was the source who had secretly supplied Bob Woodward of The Washington Post with crucial leads in the Watergate affair in the early nineteen seventies.
28 7 6 2776 His decision to unmask himself, in an article in Vanity Fair, ended a guessing game that had gone on for more than 30 years.
28 7 7 2777 The disclosure even surprised Woodward and his partner on the Watergate story, Carl Bernstein.
28 7 8 2778 They had kept their promise not to reveal his identity until after his death.
28 7 9 2779 Indeed, Woodward was so scrupulous about shielding Felt that he did not introduce him to Bernstein until this year, 36 years after they cracked the scandal.
28 7 10 2780 The three met for two hours one afternoon in November in Santa Rosa, where Felt had retired.
28 7 11 2781 The reporters likened it to a family reunion.
28 7 12 2782 Felt played a dual role in Nixon's downfall.
28 7 13 2783 As a secret informant, he kept the story alive in the press.
28 7 14 2784 As associate director of the FBI, he fought the president's efforts to obstruct the FBI's investigation of the Watergate break-in.
28 7 15 2785 Felt later said he believed that Nixon had been misusing the FBI for political advantage.
28 7 16 2786 He knew that Nixon wanted the Watergate affair to vanish.
28 7 17 2787 He knew that the White House had ordered the CIA to tell the bureau, on grounds of national security, to stand down in its felony investigation of the June 1972 break-in.
28 7 18 2788 He saw that order as an effort to obstruct justice, and he rejected it.
28 7 19 2789 That resistance led indirectly to Nixon's resignation.
28 7 20 2790 Passed up for promotion
28 7 21 2791 Felt had expected to be named to succeed J. Edgar Hoover, who had run the bureau for 48 years and died in May 1972.
28 7 22 2792 The president instead chose a politically loyal Justice Department official, L. Patrick Gray, who later followed orders from the White House to destroy documents in the case.
28 7 23 2793 The choice infuriated Felt.
28 7 24 2794 He later wrote that the president ``wanted a politician in J. Edgar Hoover's position who would convert the bureau into an adjunct of the White House machine.''
28 7 25 2795 Hoover had sworn off break-ins without warrants - ``black bag jobs,'' he called them - in 1966, after carrying them out at the FBI for four decades.
28 7 26 2796 The Nixon White House hired its own operatives to steal information, plant eavesdropping equipment and hunt down the sources of leaks.
28 7 27 2797 The Watergate break-in took place six weeks after Hoover died.
28 7 28 2798 While Watergate was seething, Felt authorized nine illegal break-ins at the homes of friends and relatives of members of the Weather Underground, a violent left-wing splinter group.
28 7 29 2799 The people he chose as targets had committed no crimes.
28 7 30 2800 The FBI had no search warrants.
28 7 31 2801 He later said he ordered the break-ins because he felt national security required it.
28 7 32 2802 In a criminal trial, Felt was convicted in November 1980 of conspiring to violate the constitutional rights of Americans. 
28 7 33 2803 Nixon, who had denounced him in private for leaking Watergate secrets, testified on his behalf.
28 7 34 2804 Called by the prosecution, he told the jury that presidents and by extension their officers had an inherent right to conduct illegal searches in the name of national security.
28 7 35 2805 ``As Deep Throat, Felt helped establish the principle that our highest government officials are subject to the Constitution and the laws of the land,'' the prosecutor, John W. Nields, wrote in The Washington Post in 2005.
28 7 36 2806 ``Yet when it came to the Weather Underground bag jobs, he seems not to have been aware that this same principle applied to him.''
28 7 37 2807 Seven months after the conviction, President Ronald Reagan pardoned Felt.
28 7 38 2808 Then 67, Felt celebrated the decision as one of great symbolic value.
28 7 39 2809 ``This is going to be the biggest shot in the arm for the intelligence community for a long time,'' he said.
28 7 40 2810 After the pardon, Nixon sent him a congratulatory bottle of champagne.
28 7 41 2811 Felt then disappeared from public view for a quarter of a century, denying unequivocally, time and again, that he had been Deep Throat.
28 7 42 2812 It was a lie he told to serve what he believed to be a higher truth.
28 7 43 2813 William Mark Felt was born in Twin Falls, Idaho, on Aug. 17, 1913. 
28 7 44 2814 After graduating from the University of Idaho, he was drawn to public service in Washington and went to work for Sen. James P. Pope, D-Idaho.
28 7 45 2815 In 1938, he married his college sweetheart, Audrey Robinson, in Washington.
28 7 46 2816 They were wed by the chaplain of the House of Representatives.
28 7 47 2817 She died in 1984.
28 7 48 2818 The couple had a daughter, Joan, and a son, Mark.
28 7 49 2819 They and four grandsons survive Felt.
28 7 50 2820 Days before Pearl Harbor, after earning a law degree in night classes at George Washington University, Felt applied to the FBI and joined it in January 1942.
28 7 51 2821 He spent most of World War II hunting German spies.
28 7 52 2822 After stints in Seattle, New Orleans and Los Angeles, Hoover named him special agent in charge of the Salt Lake City and Kansas City offices in the late nineteen fifties.
28 7 53 2823 Rising to high positions at the headquarters in the 1960s, he oversaw the training of FBI agents and conducted internal investigations as chief of the inspection division.
28 7 54 2824 In early 1970, while waiting in an anteroom of the West Wing of the White House, Felt chanced to meet a Navy lieutenant delivering classified messages to the National Security Council staff.
28 7 55 2825 The young man in dress blues was Bob Woodward.
28 7 56 2826 By his own description fiercely ambitious and in need of adult guidance, Woodward tried to wring career counseling from his elder.
28 7 57 2827 He left the White House with the number to Felt's direct line at the FBI
28 7 58 2828 On July 1, 1971, Hoover promoted Felt to deputy associate director, the third in command at the headquarters, beneath Hoover's right-hand man and longtime companion, Clyde A. Tolson.
28 7 59 2829 With both of his superiors in poor health, Felt increasingly took effective command of the daily work of the FBI.
28 7 60 2830 When Hoover died and Tolson retired, he saw his path to power cleared.
28 7 61 2831 But Nixon denied him, and he seethed with frustrated ambition in summer 1972.
28 7 62 2832 Breaking Watergate
28 7 63 2833 One evening that summer, a few weeks after the Watergate break-in, Woodward, then a neophyte newspaperman, knocked on Felt's door in pursuit of the story.
28 7 64 2834 Felt decided to cooperate with him and set up an elaborate system of espionage techniques for clandestine meetings with Woodward.
28 7 65 2835 If Woodward needed to talk, he would move a flowerpot planted with a red flag on the balcony of his apartment on P Street in Washington.
28 7 66 2836 If Felt had a message, Woodward's home-delivered New York Times would arrive with an inked circle on Page 20.
28 7 67 2837 Woodward would leave his apartment by the back alley that night and take one taxi to a downtown hotel, then a second to an underground parking garage in the Rosslyn section of Arlington, Virginia.
28 7 68 2838 Within weeks, Felt steered The Post to a story establishing that the Watergate break-in was part of ``a massive campaign of political spying and sabotage'' directed by the White House.
28 7 69 2839 For the next eight months, he did his best to keep the newspaper on the trail, largely by providing, on ``deep background,'' anonymous confirmation of facts reporters had gathered from others.
28 7 70 2840 The Post's managing editor, Howard Simons, gave him his famous pseudonym, taken from the pornographic movie then in vogue.
28 7 71 2841 Millions of Americans knew him only as a shadowy figure in the 1976 movie made from the Watergate saga, ``All the President's Men,'' which made ``Woodward and Bernstein'' legends of American journalism.
28 7 72 2842 In the movie, Deep Throat (Hal Holbrook) gives Woodward (Robert Redford) probably the most famous bit of free advice in the history of investigative journalism.
28 7 73 2843 It was a three-word road map to the heart of the matter: ``Follow the money.''
28 7 74 2844 Felt never said it.
28 7 75 2845 It was part of the myth that surrounded Deep Throat.
28 8 1 2846 Mark ``Deep Throat'' Felt Dead at 95
28 8 2 2847 W. Mark Felt, Sr., the number 2 man at the FBI during the Watergate <MENTION CHAIN="2">scandal</MENTION> , <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> yesterday from Alzheimer's disease at a hospice near his home in Santa Rosa, California, the Washington Post reports.
28 8 3 2848 Felt was an instrumental player in the stunning downfall of President Nixon, but his identity as ``Deep Throat'' -reporter Bob Woodard's anonymous source for the Post's bombshell series of scoops on the Watergate affair in 1972-was unknown until three years ago, when Felt's family unmasked him in the pages of Vanity Fair.
28 8 4 2849 According to the Times, even Woodward was shocked at this; 
28 8 5 2850 he had gaurded the secret so zealously that even his partner Carl Bernstein did not meet Felt until earlier this year.
28 8 6 2851 Felt never revealed why he leaked details on the Watergate break-in and cover up to Woodward, but the Times obituary points out that in May 1972 Feld had been passed over by Nixon as Edgar Hoover's successor to run the bureau.
28 9 1 2852 W. Mark Felt, who remained anonymous for more than three decades as the source known as ``Deep Throat'' in the 1972 Watergate <MENTION CHAIN="2">scandal</MENTION> that <MENTION CHAIN="5">toppled</MENTION> Richard Nixon's presidency, has <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION>.
28 9 2 2853 Felt <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> at his home in Santa Rosa, California, Thursday, the Press Democrat newspaper reported, citing Felt's grandson Nick Jones.
28 9 3 2854 Felt provided tips and information that guided Washington Post reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein as they wrote stories stemming from the bungled burglary of the Democratic Party National Committee headquarters in 1972.
28 9 4 2855 President Nixon ultimately resigned as a consequence of the White House role in the scandal and in the cover-up that followed.
28 9 5 2856 The identity of Felt, a former associate director at the Federal Bureau of Investigation, remained a secret until May 2005, when Woodward and Bernstein confirmed revelations published in an article in the July issue of Vanity Fair.
28 9 6 2857 ``Because of his position virtually atop the chief investigative agency, his words and guidance had immense, at times even staggering, authority,'' Woodward said in an article in the Washington Post on June 2, 2005.
28 9 7 2858 The story of ``Deep Throat,'' a name borrowed from the title of a 1972 pornographic film, assumed legendary status as academics and history buffs clamored to unlock the enigma that played a role in Nixon's resignation in 1974.
28 9 8 2859 As early as October 1972, Nixon himself voiced suspicion that Felt may be leaking information to the press and Attorney General Richard Kleindienst had pressured FBI Acting Director L. Patrick Gray to fire his deputy.
28 9 9 2860 Felt denied his role repeatedly and stayed at the FBI until his retirement in June 1973.
28 9 10 2861 ``The thing that stuns me is that the goddamn secret has lasted this long,'' Ben Bradlee, who oversaw almost 400 stories on Watergate when he was the Washington Post's executive editor, said after the May 2005 revelations.
28 9 11 2862 Although he knew the paper's source was a high-ranking government official, Bradlee didn't find out Felt's name until Nixon resigned.
28 9 12 2863 Felt was one of many people rumored to be ``Deep Throat.''
28 9 13 2864 Others included Alexander Haig, Nixon's White House chief of staff; former National Security Adviser Henry Kissinger; Fred Fielding, assistant to White House Counsel John Dean; and George H.W. Bush, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations at the time.
28 9 14 2865 Speculation also surrounded former U.S. Supreme Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist, whose poor health coincided with unfounded reports that ``Deep Throat'' was gravely ill.
