3 1 1 3082 After more than three years and a tangled trail of frustrating legal <MENTION CHAIN="1">delays</MENTION>, the man who <MENTION CHAIN="2">killed</MENTION> four people in a brazen courthouse <MENTION CHAIN="3">escape</MENTION> was <MENTION CHAIN="4">sentenced</MENTION> Saturday to prison for life without parole and hundreds of years more.
3 1 2 3083 Yet prosecutors who spent the last month urging jurors to sentence one of Atlanta's most notorious criminals to death were not celebrating.
3 1 3 3084 ``The community has spoken,'' Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard said at an emotional press conference after the sentencing of Brian Nichols.
3 1 4 3085 ``Even though we are puzzled and terribly disappointed by the decision, we must accept the conclusion provided by our community.''
3 1 5 3086 It showed how difficult it is to get a capital sentence in Atlanta's Fulton County, where death penalties are rare even in a state where support for capital punishment is widespread.
3 1 6 3087 Georgia tied for third in carrying out executions last year.
3 1 7 3088 And it underscored the problems Georgia prosecutors say they frequently face with the requirement that death sentences can only be returned by unanimous jury verdicts.
3 1 8 3089 Nichols, 37, was found guilty last month of murdering a judge, a court reporter, a sheriff's deputy and a federal agent in the March 2005 rampage.
3 1 9 3090 After four days deliberating on whether to recommend the death penalty, the jury deadlocked at 9-3. 
3 1 10 3091 Nichols will likely die in prison after Superior Court Judge James Bodiford handed down the maximum prison sentence on each of 54 charges.
3 1 11 3092 The deadlock devastated prosecutors, who had turned down an offer from Nichols' attorneys to plead guilty in exchange for a life sentence. 
3 1 12 3093 The trial has already cost more than $2 million, likely the most expensive in state history.
3 1 13 3094 And it may not be over yet:
3 1 14 3095 Howard said he's talked to the U.S. Attorney about a federal death penalty trial for the federal agent's slaying.
3 1 15 3096 In the meantime, Howard and some state legislative leaders said Georgia's death penalty rules should be changed.
3 1 16 3097 ``Georgia is a conservative state, but there are pockets where it is not,'' said state Rep. Barry Fleming, a Republican who led a failed bid last year to allow judges to approve death penalties even if one or two jurors voted against it.
3 1 17 3098 ``There are people who will attempt to nullify the law when they get on the jury.''
3 1 18 3099 The last time a Fulton County jury issued a death sentence was eight years ago, and only then for a triple murderer who killed a toddler.
3 1 19 3100 One factor could be race.
3 1 20 3101 The county is 43 percent black, and numerous polls and surveys have found that blacks are more likely than whites to oppose capital punishment.
3 1 21 3102 Eight of the jurors were black.
3 1 22 3103 The three who voted against the death penalty would not comment, but Howard said other jurors told him the three holdouts refused to deliberate.
3 1 23 3104 He said he was told that one was wearing headphones during the closed-door discussions this week.
3 1 24 3105 Two jurors who spoke at Howard's news conference but declined to be identified said they worked hard to try to reach a verdict.
3 1 25 3106 ``I believe Brian Nichols did not win.
3 1 26 3107 In his own words, he said it's not his DNA to stay in jail, which is what he has to look forward to the rest of his life,'' said Christina Greenway, daughter of slain court reporter Julie Ann Brandau.
3 1 27 3108 ``I'm not disappointed and I have no regrets.''
3 1 28 3109 Nichols was being escorted to his trial for rape when he overpowered a deputy guarding him and stole her gun.
3 1 29 3110 He burst into the courtroom and shot and killed Superior Court Judge Rowland Barnes, Brandau and sheriff's Deputy Hoyt Teasley.
3 1 30 3111 He fled downtown Atlanta and managed to evade hundreds of police officers searching for him overnight.
3 1 31 3112 In Atlanta's posh Buckhead neighborhood, he shot and killed federal agent David Wilhelm at a house the agent was renovating.
3 1 32 3113 Death penalty experts said the Nichols verdict shows there's no telling what will happen when a jury is asked to settle a capital case.
3 1 33 3114 ``It's very hard for 12 people to sit down around the table to make a decision to put another human being to death,'' said Stephen Bright, a Yale Law School lecturer and a veteran capital defense attorney.
3 1 34 3115 Nichols, who argued he was insane when he carried out the killings, spoke for the first time in court on Saturday as relatives of the victims' families quietly wept.
3 1 35 3116 ``I just wanted to say that I know that the things I've done caused a lot of pain and I'm sorry,'' he said.
3 1 36 3117 ``And I just wanted to say that I will not bring dishonor to the decision to spare my life.
3 1 37 3118 That's it.''
3 1 38 3119 The judge had advice for anyone who deals with Nichols in the future:
3 1 39 3120 ``Do not trust Mr. Nichols ever again.
3 1 40 3121 Ever again.
3 1 41 3122 Because he cannot be trusted.''
3 2 1 3123 Now that Fulton County courthouse killer Brian Nichols has been <MENTION CHAIN="4">sentenced</MENTION> to life without parole, one of the not yet answered questions is where the 37-year-old will <MENTION CHAIN="5">serve</MENTION> time.
3 2 2 3124 Superior Court Judge James Bodiford on Saturday suggested that Nichols should serve his time in the federal maximum security prison - known as Supermax - in Florence, Colo., which has the reputation as the nation's toughest and most secure prison.
3 2 3 3125 Bodiford said he was surprised to learn during the trial that Nichols, who is committed of state crimes, could still serve his time in a federal prison.
3 2 4 3126 ``I thought maybe Supermax might be a good place for Mr. Nichols for what it is worth,'' Bodiford said.
3 2 5 3127 ``I don't believe I can order it and I am not going to order it but that is my two cents worth.''
3 2 6 3128 About the prison:
3 2 7 3129 The supermax unit at the Florence Federal Correctional Complex at Florence, Colo., primarily holds extremely dangerous or escape-risk federal inmates.
3 2 8 3130 There also are a few state prisoners there who need more security than those prisons can provide.
3 2 9 3131 The remote prison, which opened in 1994, almost disappears into the same-color desert around it.
3 2 10 3132 Cells are 8-by-12 feet, with concrete walls, ceilings and furnishings, including the bed.
3 2 11 3133 The toilets, sinks and showers are stainless steel.
3 2 12 3134 Cell windows are long and narrow, limiting the view to only the sky.
3 2 13 3135 Some known inmates:
3 2 14 3136 Unabomber Ted Kaczynski, shoe bomber Richard Reid, and Sept. 11, 2001 conspirator Zacarias Moussaoui.
3 2 15 3137 Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, the 1960s militant once named H. Rap Brown, convicted in Georgia of the state crime of murdering a Fulton County deputy.
3 2 16 3138 Convicted of federal crimes in Georgia: Eric Robert Rudolph, who pleaded guilty to the Centennial Olympic Park bombings and other bombings in Atlanta, and Malachi Z. York, the Nuwaubian leader convicted of child molestation, racketeering and federal financial reporting charges.
3 2 17 3139 Prison program:
3 2 18 3140 A three-step program limits - or perhaps deprives - inmates of many things that would stimulate the senses - smell, sight and touch.
3 2 19 3141 Olympic Park bomber Rudolph complained in letters to a Colorado newspaper in 2006 that the prison's design was driving him insane.
3 2 20 3142 In the first stage of the program, inmates spend 23 of every 24 hours double-locked behind a steel door and a barred grate.
3 2 21 3143 They are allowed one 15-minute telephone call a month. 
3 2 22 3144 One hour each day is spent alone in a recreation area.
3 2 23 3145 Their behavior is reviewed every 90 days before they can be moved up to the next step.
3 2 24 3146 At the second and third steps, inmates are given progressively more freedom, more time for exercise, longer and more frequent telephone calls and more social contact with other prisoners - as long as they are free of violations.
3 2 25 3147 Limited inmate privileges:
3 2 26 3148 Inmates get a radio and a black-and-white, 13-inch television made specially with clear backs that reveal all internal components. 
3 2 27 3149 The TVs are hooked up to ``basic cable.''
3 2 28 3150 Inmates participate in religious services that are broadcast on their televisions.
3 2 29 3151 Guards pass inmates' meals, law books and other items through a slot in the door.
3 2 30 3152 There is limited direct human contact.
3 3 1 3153 Former Kutztown University football player Brian Nichols has <MENTION CHAIN="4">received</MENTION> a sentence of life in prison without parole for a March 2005 <MENTION CHAIN="2">shooting</MENTION> spree in an Atlanta courthouse, according to reports.
3 3 2 3154 According to reports in an Atlanta newspaper:
3 3 3 3155 Nichols was sentenced Saturday morning to seven life sentences and four sentences of life without parole plus 485 years.
3 3 4 3156 Nichols was being tried for rape in March 2005 when he overpowered a female sheriff's deputy, took her gun and shot the judge in his rape trial and the court reporter.
3 3 5 3157 Outside the courtroom, Nichols shot and killed a sheriff's deputy sergeant.
3 3 6 3158 Later that day, as he attempted to elude police, he shot and killed a U.S. Customs agent.
3 3 7 3159 He later made it to Gwinnett County where he kidnapped a woman who says she talked Nichols into surrendering.
3 4 1 3160 Fulton Courthouse killer Brian Nichols was <MENTION CHAIN="4">sentenced</MENTION> Saturday morning to seven life sentences and four sentences of life without parole plus 485 years for the <MENTION CHAIN="2">crimes</MENTION> he committed on March 11, 2005, that stunned metro Atlanta and the nation.
3 4 2 3161 Brian Nichols was saved from a death sentence by three jurors who were determined that he instead spend his life in prison, no matter how many people he killed.
3 4 3 3162 Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard suggested Saturday that the possibility of a death penalty was doomed - even before jury selection - by the three holdouts.
3 4 4 3163 ``I talked to two jurors and they both say that some people showed up for jury duty with their minds already made up and never entered into a meaningful discussion of a death sentence,'' Howard said Saturday after Nichols was sentenced.
3 4 5 3164 ``That means we didn't get a fair trial.''
3 4 6 3165 The two jurors, who indicated they were among the nine voting to put Nichols to death, reported one of the holdouts even worked a crossword puzzle while the panel deliberated Nichols' fate for 40 hours over four days.
3 4 7 3166 The frustrated prosecutor gambled on getting a death penalty decision when he denied a Nichols offer a year ago to plead guilty in exchange for a life prison sentence.
3 4 8 3167 He said Saturday that he would urge Georgia lawmakers to amend the law - that now requires a unanimous decision - to allow a 10-juror majority approve a death penalty.
3 4 9 3168 ``We're not asking for favors - we are just asking for a level playing field,'' Howard said.
3 4 10 3169 ``People who will not deliberate should not be permitted to continue to serve on juries.''
3 4 11 3170 He was especially vexed because the holdouts were evidently not truthful when questioned by lawyers about whether they could impose the death penalty before they were chosen for the jury.
3 4 12 3171 He said all the jurors swore under oath that they could consider death for Nichols if they felt the crimes deserved it.
3 4 13 3172 Inside the jury room, however, the three holdouts told the other nine jurors that they would not impose death for any killings.
3 4 14 3173 In fact, Howard said, the nine pro-death jurors asked the three holdouts how many people would Nichols have to kill before they would be willing to vote for execution.
3 4 15 3174 ``They asked, 'How about if it had been 50 people?''' Howard said.
3 4 16 3175 ``And the three people said it wouldn't make any difference at all.''
3 4 17 3176 The two female jurors, one white and one black, spoke publicly at a news conference Saturday to express their exasperation
3 4 18 3177 ``I want the families to know we did everything we could do,`` said the white woman, who was identified as Juror No. 12.
3 4 19 3178 Family members of the four murder victims expressed outrage that Nichols had escaped the death penalty.
3 4 20 3179 ``I feel in some ways he is proud of what he did,'' said Deborah Teasley, widow of a sheriff's deputy Nichols murdered.
3 4 21 3180 ``He was constantly sitting there at the defense table with a smirk on his face.''
3 4 22 3181 The two jurors, who did not give their names, said the closed-door jury deliberations never became hostile during the four days they tried to decide a penalty.
3 4 23 3182 ``Everyone was respectful,`` said Juror No. 8, one of six African-American women on the panel.
3 4 24 3183 ``We were able to state our opinions.
3 4 25 3184 But we would not back down.''
3 4 26 3185 It was the pro-death majority, hoping to sway the three holdouts, who sought the replay of the bombshell jailhouse tape recording of Nichols talking with his brother on a telephone call.
3 4 27 3186 ``We were searching,'' Juror No. 12 said.
3 4 28 3187 An angry Nichols was recorded saying he didn't regret the four murders and would have taken his rampage to the DA's office in the courthouse if given the chance again.
3 4 29 3188 Defense attorneys vehemently objected to the tape as ``highly prejudicial,'' though Judge James Bodiford said jurors could rehear just the portion played for them at trial.
3 4 30 3189 In the end, the jury did not follow through with a formal written request for the tape.
3 4 31 3190 The two jurors kept their public comments limited at the news conference.
3 4 32 3191 Other jurors contacted by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, including the jury foreman, declined to talk or answer questions left for them at their residences.
3 4 33 3192 The jury - six black women, two white women, two black men, one white man and one Asian man - began hearing the case Sept. 22 and convicted Nichols on Nov. 7 after 12 hours of deliberation.
3 4 34 3193 The trial then entered a four-week penalty phase, with prosecution witnesses testifying that Nichols is still a remorseless killer plotting constantly to escape, and defense witnesses testifying he had a troubled childhood and has shown signs of remorse and redemption.
3 4 35 3194 Howard said the jurors in the majority told him after reporting their 9-3 deadlock to Bodiford that they did not know they could have asked Bodiford to replace with alternates the three who refused to deliberate with them.
3 4 36 3195 On Friday morning, a day after the 9-3 deadlock was first reported, prosecutor Kellie Hill asked Bodiford to ask the jury if all of the jurors were participating in good faith.
3 4 37 3196 Defense lawyers objected, arguing to Bodiford that any such inquiry during the penalty phase would amount to coercion - which could result in a reversal on appeal.
3 4 38 3197 Josh Moore, one of the defense lawyers, had reminded the judge earlier that unanimity in the penalty phase was not required.
3 4 39 3198 ``Georgia law shows no preference for a unanimous verdict in the sentencing phase of a death case,'' he said.
3 4 40 3199 Howard said state law is murky on whether a judge could inquire or replace jurors during the penalty phase.
3 4 41 3200 The law also permits each juror to follow his or her personal morality on determining whether to impose a death sentence, as long as the juror can honestly consider it.
3 4 42 3201 Howard said he hoped the Legislature also would change the law, which permits vague responses during jury selection on whether potential jurors would be willing to impose the death penalty.
3 4 43 3202 Victims' relatives said any Nichols victory was hollow.
3 4 44 3203 ``I don't think Brian Nichols won,'' said Christina Greenway, daughter of the court reporter Nichols murdered.
3 4 45 3204 ``In his own words, it is not in his DNA to stay in prison.
3 4 46 3205 Now he can look forward to a life in prison.''
3 4 47 3206 Nichols rose to infamy when he escaped from custody at the Fulton County Courthouse during his rape trial on March 11, 2005, by overpowering his guard, sheriff's Deputy Cynthia Hall, beating her so badly he left her brain-damaged and blind in one eye.
3 4 48 3207 Nichols then took her gun and went to the chambers of Superior Court Judge Rowland Barnes, who was presiding over his trial, and took the staff captive and seized the gun of another deputy.
3 4 49 3208 Minutes later, he shot Barnes in the back of the head while he was on the bench hearing a civil matter.
3 4 50 3209 Four seconds later, he shot the court reporter, Julie Ann Brandau, in the head, killing her, also.
3 4 51 3210 Nichols then escaped and shot and killed Deputy Sgt. Hoyt Teasley, who had pursued him outside the courthouse.
3 4 52 3211 Nichols committed a series of carjackings before finally escaping downtown Atlanta by taking MARTA to Buckhead while police looked for him.
3 4 53 3212 In Buckhead, while in search of a hiding place, he committed other assaults before ending up that night at the house that David Wilhelm was building a few blocks from Lenox Mall.
3 4 54 3213 He shot Wilhelm, an off-duty U.S. Customs agent, emptied his pockets of cash and took his cellphone as he lay paralyzed, dying on the floor.
3 4 55 3214 Nichols stole Wilhelm's pickup truck, where he said he found Wilhelm's badge.
3 4 56 3215 Whether he knew Wilhelm was a federal agent before he killed him could make a difference on whether federal authorities indict him and seek a death penalty in a federal court.
3 4 57 3216 At trial, prosecutors contended Nichols ambushed Wilhelm and that he didn't have his gun drawn during the confrontation as Nichols claimed.
3 4 58 3217 Defense lawyers contended that Nichols committed the crimes because he suffered from a delusion that made him believe he was leading a slave revolt against an unjust justice system.
3 4 59 3218 Nichols, 37, was an $80,000-a-year computer system expert at UPS before his life spiraled out of control after his girlfriend of seven years dumped him for infidelity.
3 4 60 3219 He took her captive and raped her in August 2004 - saying he wanted to win her back - and was arrested and spent nine months in jail before the killings.
3 4 61 3220 Wilhelm's widow, Candee, took aim at Nichols' parents - who had won praise from the judge as solid citizens - when she addressed the public after the sentencing.
3 4 62 3221 ``Brian Nichols' parents raised an extremely evil person,'' said Wilhelm, who was briefly detained during the trial for bringing a pistol into the courthouse.
3 4 63 3222 ``I am extremely disappointed that the defendant has been shown the mercy that he did not show on March 11, 2005.''
3 4 64 3223 Lead prosecutor Kellie Hill reminded the crowd that mercy did not equal injustice.
3 4 65 3224 ``Justice has been served in this case - it absolutely has been,'' Hill said.
3 4 66 3225 ``Sometimes we don't understand the outcome, but we all have to accept it.''
3 4 67 3226 Nichols' mother, Claritha, and father, Gene, attended the trial most days for 12 weeks.
3 4 68 3227 They became the focus of testimony about their son's upbringing, and his mother testified about events leading up to his rape trial on the day he escaped and went on his killing spree.
3 4 69 3228 They sat through the sentencing Saturday but left the courthouse before reporters could interview them.
3 4 70 3229 As she came into the courthouse before the sentencing, Nichols' mother expressed their sentiments.
3 4 71 3230 ``We just want to fade into obscurity,'' she said.
