30 2 11 3427 Many countries were <MENTION CHAIN="1">affected</MENTION> by the <MENTION CHAIN="3">outage</MENTION>, including India, Saudi Arabia, Egypt and Malaysia, which all <MENTION CHAIN="4">lost</MENTION> a significant percentage on their voice traffic to Europe.
30 2 12 3428 For example, 82 percent of India's voice traffic capability to Europe was out of service early Friday, although that situation has now improved, the spokeswoman said.
30 2 13 3429 Internet traffic also has been <MENTION CHAIN="1">hit</MENTION> by the incident, according to Danny McPherson, chief security officer with Arbor Networks.
30 2 14 3430 His company's sensors reported that between 3,000 and 5,000 Internet routes in the region were off-line early Friday morning.
30 2 15 3431 These routes are the Internet's equivalent of dialing prefixes, meaning that computers that used them would be completely unreachable until service was restored.
30 2 16 3432 ``It's significant that it was lost,'' he said
30 2 17 3433 ``For them it was in the middle of a business day on Friday.''
30 2 18 3434 A large number of these came back on-line around 17:00 UTC, McPherson said.
30 2 19 3435 Most likely this happened after ISPs (Internet service providers) that had been knocked off-line had found alternate routes for their traffic.
30 2 20 3436 It's hard to estimate how many Internet users were affected by the cut, but the Internet has a total of close to 300,000 such routes, he said.
30 2 21 3437 This is not the first time this year that these cables have been cut.
30 2 22 3438 Earlier this year both the Sea Me We 4 and Flag cables were cut.
30 2 23 3439 Flag's cable was reportedly cut by ships anchored off the coast of Alexandria, Egypt.
30 3 1 3440 Damaged cables cause internet outages for millions
30 3 2 3441 Up to 70% of communications to the Middle East have been <MENTION CHAIN="1">disrupted</MENTION> after cables connecting region to Europe were <MENTION CHAIN="2">damaged</MENTION> 
30 3 3 3442 Millions of web users across the Middle East are struggling to get online after <MENTION CHAIN="2">damage</MENTION> to undersea cables connecting Europe, Africa and Asia <MENTION CHAIN="5">took</MENTION> down a major route for internet traffic.
30 3 4 3443 As much as 70% of internet traffic and telephone communications between the continents has been <MENTION CHAIN="1">affected</MENTION> by the <MENTION CHAIN="3">outage</MENTION>.
30 3 5 3444 It is believed to have been caused by damage to a string of cables which run on the bed of the Mediterranean Sea between Italy and Egypt, connecting Europe with other parts of the world.
30 3 6 3445 The lines, which run hit the Egyptian coast at Alexandria and go on to connect to Asia, are responsible for carrying vast amounts of internet traffic and phone calls between different parts of the world.
30 3 7 3446 It remains unclear what precisely what caused the <MENTION CHAIN="2">damage</MENTION>, but the Egyptian communications ministry said that ships have already been <MENTION CHAIN="6">dispatched</MENTION> to look at the problem - although <MENTION CHAIN="7">repairs</MENTION> will take ``several days''.
30 3 8 3447 Jonathan Wright, a director at telecoms company Interoute, said that the <MENTION CHAIN="3">outage</MENTION> could have a devastating <MENTION CHAIN="1">affect</MENTION> on business and communication around the world.
30 3 9 3448 ``The potential impact of an outage of this size cannot be underestimated - it is like severing a major artery,'' he said. 
30 3 10 3449 ``Global internet connectivity is reliant on sub-sea cables connecting countries.''
30 3 11 3450 The incident comes less than a year after a similar outage brought a halt to communications between Europe, Africa and Asia.
30 3 12 3451 Those problems were believed to have been caused by ships' anchors ripping through another section of the same cables, but were exacerbated by simultaneous damage in lines through the Middle East.
30 3 13 3452 As many as 75 million people were affected in countries as far apart as India, Egypt and Dubai.
30 3 14 3453 It is not yet clear whether today's outage is the same order of magnitude.
30 3 15 3454 Despite the prevalence of wireless internet and satellite connections, global communications are still largely reliant on the vast webs of fibre optic cables which cover the planet.
30 3 16 3455 The lines, which take years of planning to install, move traffic backwards and forwards across continents.
30 3 17 3456 The cables hit by the latest incident are among the most vital information pipelines linking Europe to the rest of the world - and are responsible for the majority of all connectivity in the Middle East and south Asia.
30 3 18 3457 According to Alan Mauldin, research director of communications analysis company TeleGeography, the succession of problems in the region are only likely to be remedied by a series of new cables which are currently being planned.
30 3 19 3458 ``Many new cable systems are slated to enter service between Europe and Egypt in the next few years,'' he said.
