31 7 1 3756 Hansbrough broke UNC's career scoring record the Carolina way
31 7 2 3757 During the spring of 1977, North Carolina coach Dean Smith invited his star guard Phil Ford, who had just completed his junior season, into his office.
31 7 3 3758 Smith told Ford that he had done some research on where Ford would be selected in the upcoming NBA draft. Based on that information, he recommended to Ford that he leave school.
31 7 4 3759 Ford didn't even have to think about it.
31 7 5 3760 He told Smith right away that he wasn't interested.
31 7 6 3761 ``At the time, a lot of people weren't doing that, so going pro wasn't something I had even considered at all,'' Ford says.
31 7 7 3762 ``The financial situation was different back then as well.
31 7 8 3763 At the time, my parents were teachers, so getting my degree was very important to me.
31 7 9 3764 The opportunity wasn't worth me not getting my degree.''
31 7 10 3765 Last April, Tyler Hansbrough faced a similar decision, but under much different circumstances.
31 7 11 3766 Hansbrough plays in an era when not only is it common for undergraduates to turn pro, but in some circles a player is considered a failure if he stays past his junior year.
31 7 12 3767 Needless to say, he faced a financial opportunity much greater than the one Ford confronted three decades ago.
31 7 13 3768 Hansbrough spent two full weeks torturing himself over the impending decision.
31 7 14 3769 When Hansbrough finally told Roy Williams he wanted to return for his senior year, he felt like the weight of the world was off his shoulders.
31 7 15 3770 He was so relieved that he didn't even leave the weight room when Williams asked him to come to his office so they could craft a press release.
31 7 16 3771 ``It was a stressful process,'' Hansbrough said in mid-October.
31 7 17 3772 ``You're thinking about what you're going to do with the rest of your life.
31 7 18 3773 Every time I thought about leaving, I thought about how much I'd miss coming home, living with my teammates and doing a lot of the fun things we do.
31 7 19 3774 I just felt like coming back would be the best situation for me.''
31 7 20 3775 In considering that life decision, it's doubtful Hansbrough gave much thought to the chance he would have to become North Carolina's alltime scoring leader if he returned.
31 7 21 3776 Still, given the century's worth of tradition that has reigned in Chapel Hill, it was no small feat that Hansbrough <MENTION CHAIN="5">accomplished</MENTION> Thursday night, when he <MENTION CHAIN="5">broke</MENTION> Ford's school career scoring mark with less than eight minutes to play in the first half of North Carolina's <MENTION CHAIN="2">game</MENTION> against Evansville
31 7 22 3777 North Carolina has established itself as the gold standard of college basketball, and in the soft-spoken, hard-charging, 6-foot-9 power forward from Poplar Bluff, Missouri, this proud program has a worthy standard bearer.
31 7 23 3778 Ford is correct when he says that people aren't appreciative enough of Hansbrough's skills, but there is no doubt that what sets this young man apart is the intensity with which he plays.
31 7 24 3779 If Ford was a classical symphony, Hansbrough is a heavy metal rock concert, powering, jostling, banging, and always, always out-hustling his opponent en route to the basket.
31 7 25 3780 It is instructive that while Hansbrough remains ninth on the ACC's alltime scoring list, he is already the league's career leader in free throws attempted.
31 7 26 3781 If he stays healthy, he will likely leave North Carolina as the school's alltime rebounds king.
31 7 27 3782 More than anything, though, Tyler Hansbrough deserves this record because he came back to school.
31 7 28 3783 This is not to disparage players like Michael Jordan, Antawn Jamison and Rashad McCants who might have had a shot at Ford's mark had they stayed.
31 7 29 3784 But at a place like North Carolina, which embodies team play, the scoring record should belong to a four-year player.
31 7 30 3785 Hansbrough would probably not have been a top-five draft pick had he left, but it's unlikely he will signifcantly improve his draft status by playing another year.
31 7 31 3786 Also, at the time Hansbrough made his decision he was assuming that at least one of his fellow undergraduates, and as many as three of them, would be turning pro, diminishing the Tar Heels' chances of winning a championship.
31 7 32 3787 Hansbrough came back anyway, and for all the right reasons.
31 7 33 3788 Ford also points out that because freshmen were not eligible to play varsity ball from 1954-73, a huge swath of mega talents who suited up for UNC didn't have the chance to hold onto this record -- including the man Ford passed, Lenny Rosenbluth, who still holds the school's record for career scoring average (26.9) and is fourth in points scored.
31 7 34 3789 Hansbrough is sixth on the school's career scoring average list at 20.2.
31 7 35 3790 Still, it takes a special individual to eclipse a record that has stood at a place like North Carolina for 30 years.
31 7 36 3791 Ford remembers little about the night he passed Rosenbluth.
31 7 37 3792 He believes he broke the record late in the first half, the game was not interrupted, and neither he nor Rosenbluth had much to say about it.
31 7 38 3793 In fact, Rosenbluth wasn't even there that night.
31 7 39 3794 When I asked Ford if he still has the game ball, he said he thought he might, but he has moved so much in recent years (he worked as an assistant coach for the Detroit Pistons and New York Knicks before joining the Charlotte Bobcats last year) that he thinks the ball may be packed away somewhere.
31 7 40 3795 ``To be honest, I was just happy to get it over with,'' Ford says.
31 7 41 3796 ``I didn't want anything distracting from the team.''
31 7 42 3797 If the circumstances were different than they were in 1978, the central tenets of the Carolina Way have endured, from Rosenbluth to Ford to Hansbrough.
31 7 43 3798 While offering his congratulations to Hansbrough, Ford is quick to add that the career scoring record is the least important mark at North Carolina.
31 7 44 3799 ``We never cared who scored the ball,'' he says, ``as long as someone with the Carolina jersey got the ball in the basket.''
31 7 45 3800 Tyler Hansbrough would be the first to agree, even as he jostles and bangs his way towards history.
31 8 1 3801 Hansbrough breaks 30-year-old UNC scoring mark
31 8 2 3802 Forward Tyler Hansbrough <MENTION CHAIN="5">broke</MENTION> North Carolina's all-time scoring record in Thursday's <MENTION CHAIN="2">game</MENTION> against Evansville.
31 8 3 3803 Phil Ford's school mark of 2,290 points <MENTION CHAIN="14">set</MENTION> in 1978 held strong amongst a plethora of talented Tar Heels over the years, but Hansbrough, who <MENTION CHAIN="10">came</MENTION> back for his senior season after being <MENTION CHAIN="11">crowned</MENTION> the National Player of the Year, <MENTION CHAIN="5">moved</MENTION> into the top spot with a tough <MENTION CHAIN="17">leaner</MENTION> in the lane with two Purple Aces defenders hanging on him with 7:42 left in the first half.
31 8 4 3804 The game was stopped and Ford was on hand to congratulate Hansbrough at half-court.
31 8 5 3805 The Missouri native suffered through a shin injury earlier in the season that forced him to miss four games.
31 8 6 3806 In the five games he played before Thursday's action, Hansbrough averaged a team-high 22.8 points to go with 7.2 rebounds.
31 8 7 3807 In 113 career games prior to Thursday, the forward has logged 20.2 points and 8.6 rebounds in just under 31 minutes an outing, while doing a lot of damage at the free throw line with nearly nine attempts per game.
31 8 8 3808 Hansbrough, who has an outside shot at edging Duke great J.J. Redick for the all-time ACC scoring record (2,769 points), has succeeded in just about every statistical category, though he is still searching for the elusive fifth national title for the program, which moved to 10-0 after its 91-73 drubbing of Evansville.
31 8 9 3809 Hansbrough finished the game with 20 points and nine rebounds.
31 9 1 3810 Hansbrough breaks UNC career scoring record
31 9 2 3811 Phil Ford stood at midcourt, waiting for Tyler Hansbrough to take the microphone and address the home crowd.
31 9 3 3812 As the reigning national player of the year walked up, Ford playfully bowed in reverence before giving him a hug.
31 9 4 3813 Now even the famed point guard who flawlessly ran Dean Smith's ``Four Corners'' offense is looking up at Hansbrough as the storied program's all-time leading scorer.
31 9 5 3814 Hansbrough <MENTION CHAIN="4">scored</MENTION> 20 points Thursday night to <MENTION CHAIN="5">break</MENTION> Ford's 30-year-old mark and <MENTION CHAIN="6">help</MENTION> top-ranked North Carolina <MENTION CHAIN="2">beat</MENTION> Evansville 91-73, a <MENTION CHAIN="2">game</MENTION> that was completely overshadowed by the 6-foot-9 senior's record pursuit.
31 9 6 3815 He needed just nine points coming in, making the record an almost certainty considering that he's failed to reach double figures just six times in his career.
31 9 7 3816 But that didn't mean Hansbrough was oblivious to all the attention about a record that had stood through the careers of names like Michael Jordan, James Worthy and Antawn Jamison.
31 9 8 3817 ``I'm usually not nervous before games, and I was a little nervous before tonight just because I felt like there was a lot of pressure,'' said Hansbrough, who sat between Ford and coach Roy Williams during the postgame news conference.
31 9 9 3818 ``One thing for me, I didn't want us to strictly focus on trying to break a scoring record.
31 9 10 3819 We had a game and I was trying to do whatever I could to help the team.''
31 9 11 3820 Hansbrough finished 7-for-14 from the field and had nine rebounds for North Carolina (10-0), which shook off a slow start and stretched the lead to double figures against the Purple Aces (7-2) shortly after Hansbrough passed Ford midway through the first half.
31 9 12 3821 Ford, now an assistant coach to fellow Tar Heel alumnus Larry Brown with the NBA's Charlotte Bobcats, finished his career in 1978 with 2,290 points.
31 9 13 3822 ``I think everyone who knows me knows how much I love this program and to be a small part of this historic moment for Tyler is a dream come true for me,'' Ford said.
31 9 14 3823 ``I wouldn't have missed it for the world.
31 9 15 3824 ``It's an honor to be compared in the same breath with Tyler.
31 9 16 3825 When I look at how hard he plays and how he listens to Coach Williams, as a player, that's what I tried to do.''
31 9 17 3826 Hansbrough <MENTION CHAIN="15">tied</MENTION> Ford on a <MENTION CHAIN="18">jumper</MENTION> from the left wing with 14:05 left in the first half, then <MENTION CHAIN="5">set</MENTION> the record by <MENTION CHAIN="17">muscling</MENTION> in a bank <MENTION CHAIN="17">shot</MENTION> over James Haarsma and Pieter van Tongeren with 7:41 to go.
31 9 18 3827 As soon as the record-setting shot went through the net, officials briefly stopped the game to allow Ford, Williams and athletics director Dick Baddour to present Hansbrough with the game ball.
31 9 19 3828 Students who carried small signs saying ``Phil Ford 2,290'' on one side turned it around to reveal ``Tyler 2,291 +'' on the other.
31 9 20 3829 Hansbrough waved to acknowledge the roaring crowd and handled the historic moment with his typically reserved demeanor, though he seemed eager to get back to the game and away from the focus being on him.
31 9 21 3830 After the game, the school showed a video montage of Hansbrough's career highlights that included congratulations from several former players.
31 9 22 3831 That's when Hansbrough took the microphone from Ford and emotionally addressed the crowd.
31 9 23 3832 ``I never dreamed I'd be here and be the all-time leading scorer,'' Hansbrough said as he stood alone at midcourt.
31 9 24 3833 ``This is a great honor to be here and to represent you guys every night in this uniform.''
31 9 25 3834 It was a moment that fellow senior and roommate Bobby Frasor said showed how much Hansbrough appreciated the record even though he didn't want to dwell on it in recent days.
31 9 26 3835 ``I've never seen him tear up or choke up like that,'' Frasor said.
31 9 27 3836 ``But Tyler really does care about all this stuff and he knows what he accomplished is pretty special.''
31 9 28 3837 Still, the Tar Heels seemed a little tight and the home crowd anxious to see Hansbrough set the record early.
31 9 29 3838 But in the minutes afterward, the Tar Heels settled down and outscored Evansville 22-10 the rest of the half to take a 46-28 lead.
31 9 30 3839 It lightened the mood enough that Williams - who said he was counting down a player's points in his head for probably the first time - was able to tease Hansbrough on the bench after he missed a two-handed dunk on his first shot following the record.
31 9 31 3840 ``I said, 'Boy, I'm really glad that's not the basket that would've broken the record,''' he said with a laugh.
31 9 32 3841 The Tar Heels maintained a comfortable margin the rest of the way, cracking the 90-point mark for the seventh straight game.
31 9 33 3842 Hansbrough left the game for good with the Tar Heels leading 83-58 with 5:33 to play.
31 9 34 3843 He still has a chance this season to pass Sam Perkins for the program's career rebounding record and break the Atlantic Coast Conference career scoring mark set by Duke's J.J. Redick in 2006.
31 9 35 3844 ``Whatever Tyler gets, he deserves,'' Evansville coach Marty Simmons said.
31 9 36 3845 ``I've been a big fan of his since he was in high school.
31 9 37 3846 It's good to see guys that work the hardest be rewarded the most.''
