36 1 1 4232 2 leaders of polygamist group <MENTION CHAIN="1">arrested</MENTION> in Canada
36 1 2 4233 Two top leaders of a polygamous community in western Canada have been <MENTION CHAIN="1">arrested</MENTION> and <MENTION CHAIN="2">charged</MENTION> with <MENTION CHAIN="3">practicing</MENTION> polygamy, British Columbia's attorney general said Wednesday
36 1 3 4234 Attorney General Wally Oppal said Winston Blackmore is charged with marrying 20 women, while James Oler is accused of marrying two women.
36 1 4 4235 ``This has been a very complex issue,'' Oppal said.
36 1 5 4236 ``It's been with us for well over 20 years.''
36 1 6 4237 Blackmore, long known as ``the Bishop of Bountiful,'' runs an independent sect of about 400 members in the town of Bountiful.
36 1 7 4238 He once ran the Canadian arm of the Utah-based Fundamentalist Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, but was ejected in 2003 by that group's leader, Warren Jeffs.
36 1 8 4239 Oler is the bishop of Bountiful's FLDS community loyal to Jeffs.
36 1 9 4240 Even though many of the town's residents are related or have same last name, followers of the two leaders are splintered and are not allowed to talk with each other.
36 1 10 4241 FLDS members practice polygamy in arranged marriages, a tradition tied to the early theology of the Mormon church.
36 1 11 4242 Mormons renounced polygamy in 1890 as a condition of Utah's statehood.
36 1 12 4243 Last June, Oppal appointed a special prosecutor to look into allegations of criminal abuse at Bountiful despite two earlier legal opinions that said it would be difficult to proceed with criminal charges for polygamy itself.
36 1 13 4244 Blackmore openly acknowledges having numerous wives and dozens of children but has said his community abhors sexual abuse of children.
36 1 14 4245 Oppal said some legal experts believe polygamy charges will not withstand a constitutional challenge in Canada over the issue of freedom of religion.
36 1 15 4246 ``I've always taken the position that's a valid offense in law,'' Oppal said.
36 1 16 4247 ``And if someone says that it's contrary to their religion, let a judge make that decision.''
36 1 17 4248 The FLDS, with an estimated 10,000 members, is headquartered in Colorado City, Ariz., and Hildale, Utah.
36 1 18 4249 In 1947, a small group moved just across the border into Lister, British Columbia.
36 1 19 4250 The newcomers dubbed the pristine spot at the base of a snowy mountain range Bountiful.
36 1 20 4251 Besides an estimated 1,000 Canadians living in Bountiful, the U.S. Embassy estimates there are about 300 Americans there who are loyal to Blackmore and 200 others who follow Jeffs, who is in jail awaiting trial in Arizona on four counts of being an accomplice to sexual conduct with a minor.
36 2 1 4252 Polygamy <MENTION CHAIN="1">arrests</MENTION> made in Canada
36 2 2 4253 Two leaders of polygamous factions in Bountiful, British Columbia, have been <MENTION CHAIN="1">arrested</MENTION>, Canadian authorities announced.
36 2 3 4254 Jim Oler, 44, and Winston Blackmore, 52, have been charged under the criminal code with practicing polygamy, Attorney General Wally Oppal said in a statement.
36 2 4 4255 British Columbia's Royal Canadian Mounted Police have scheduled a news conference this afternoon.
36 2 5 4256 The men were <MENTION CHAIN="1">arrested</MENTION> this morning, said Sgt. Tim Shields, a media relations officer for the RCMP.
36 2 6 4257 The men were arrested this morning, said Sgt. Tim Shields, a media relations officer for the RCMP.
36 2 7 4258 Their first court appearance is scheduled for Creston Provincial Court on Jan. 21.
36 2 8 4259 Oler, accused of having two wives, is charged with ``practicing polygamy'' between Nov. 1, 2004, and Oct. 8, 2008.
36 2 9 4260 Blackmore, alleged to have 19 wives, is charged with ``practicing polygamy'' between May 1, 2005, and Dec. 8, 2006.
36 2 10 4261 Oppal said a special prosecution into allegations of criminal misconduct in the community of Bountiful, a self-named community near Creston, led to the <MENTION CHAIN="1">arrests</MENTION>.
36 2 11 4262 ``The <MENTION CHAIN="1">arrests</MENTION> are the culmination of an intensive, seven-month charge assessment <MENTION CHAIN="4">review</MENTION> by special prosecutor Terrence Robertson,'' who explored whether the men were in ``a conjungal relationship with more than one individual at a time,'' Oppal said.
36 2 12 4263 He stressed the prosecution is independent of the criminal justice branch and the Government of British Columbia, pointing out Robertson is an independent special prosecutor.
36 2 13 4264 He declined to comment on the specifics of the case.
36 2 14 4265 RCMP officers in Creston began investigating allegations of polygamy and sexual exploitation in Bountiful in the fall of 2005, Shields said in a statement.
36 2 15 4266 The community, with a population of approximately 1,000, follows the practices of the polygamous Fundamentalist Church of Jesus Christ on Latter Day Saints.
36 2 16 4267 That sect's traditional base is Hildale, Utah and Colorado City, Arizona, but its outposts include the Yearning for Zion Ranch in Eldorado, Texas.
36 2 17 4268 Texas officials raided the ranch last April and temporarily removed 439 children.
36 2 18 4269 The Canadian investigation focused on the two men in positions of authority, Shields said.
36 2 19 4270 It was completed in September 2006 with a report to Crown Counsel, which recommended charges of polygamy and sexual exploitation.
