4 1 1 4551 Bettie Page, the pin-up model whose seductive photographs in magazines titillated and outraged Americans in the 1950s, has <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION>, her agent <MENTION CHAIN="2">said</MENTION>.
4 1 2 4552 She was 85.
4 1 3 4553 ``With deep personal sadness I must announce that my dear friend and client Bettie Page passed away at 6:41pm PST this evening (0241 GMT Friday) in a Los Angeles hospital,'' her agent Mark Roesler said Thursday in a statement.
4 1 4 4554 Page suffered a heart attack nine days earlier and never regained consciousness.
4 1 5 4555 ``She captured the imagination of a generation of men and women with her free spirit and unabashed sensuality,'' Roesler said.
4 1 6 4556 Page, with shoulder-length jet-black hair and bangs, combined sweetness and sexuality in a series of now-legendary posters and photographs in the 1950s, including as one of the inaugural centerfolds in Hugh Heffner's new magazine Playboy, which named her ``the model of the century.''
4 1 7 4557 The nice-naughty image -- a sweet and beguiling smile matched with a curvacious figure and Page's propensity for burlesque films and bondage images -- proved highly combustible on the eve of America's sexual revolution.
4 1 8 4558 In the late 1950s Page became one of the most photographed women in the world, and her popularity soared even as she left the limelight nearly half a century ago.
4 1 9 4559 Page later said she was puzzled by her effect on pop culture.
4 1 10 4560 ``I have no idea why I'm the only model who has had so much fame so long after quitting work,'' she told the Los Angeles Times in 2006.
4 1 11 4561 In her old age, she refused to be photographed, preserving her mythic status.
4 1 12 4562 ``I want to be remembered, as I was when I was young and in my golden times ...
4 1 13 4563 I want to be remembered as the woman who changed people's perspectives concerning nudity in its natural form.''
4 1 14 4564 Born in 1923 in Nashville, Tennessee, Bettie Mae Page was one of six children from an impoverished family.
4 1 15 4565 After earning her university degree, she worked as a secretary and aspired to Hollywood stardom but never made it as an actress.
4 1 16 4566 A screen test at 20th Century Fox went badly, with a producer offering her a break in return for sexual favors -- she refused.
4 1 17 4567 Filmmaker and aviator Howard Hughes also doggedly pursued Page but she rebuffed him as well.
4 1 18 4568 ``I never returned any of his calls,'' she once said.
4 1 19 4569 ``I guess people will say I made a mistake.
4 1 20 4570 But sex is part of love, and you shouldn't go around doing it unless you are in love.
4 1 21 4571 I certainly didn't.''
4 1 22 4572 She posed for her first pin-up photos in 1947 and by the 1950s provocative pictures of her in bikinis or sexy lingerie were wildly popular, tacked up on the walls of locker rooms, student halls, offices and military barracks.
4 1 23 4573 Although the pictures -- which sometimes played on bondage themes -- seem tame by contemporary standards, they raised alarms in a more conservative era, prompting US senators to investigate pornography.
4 1 24 4574 Page was subpoenaed to appear before a senate committee headed by prominent Democrat Estes Kefauver but in the end never had to testify.
4 1 25 4575 For Page, the bondage photos were harmless fun.
4 1 26 4576 ``But honestly, who could take any of this seriously?'' she said years later, according to her official website.
4 1 27 4577 ``I never understood how anyone believed those poses were sexy.
4 1 28 4578 To be tied up?
4 1 29 4579 I don't get it.''
4 1 30 4580 By 1958, at the peak of her fame, Page vanished from public view and her modeling days ended.
4 1 31 4581 She became a born-again Christian but struggled with marital problems and suffered from depression and violent mood swings.
4 1 32 4582 In 1992, she left a California mental hospital having been diagnosed as a paranoid schizophrenic.
4 1 33 4583 In the 1990s, a lawyer who later became her agent, Mark Roesler, used Page's famous images for a lucrative licensing and merchandising deal that helped her financially and renewed her fame.
4 1 34 4584 The merchandise, including a clothing line, along with a film in 2005,
4 1 35 4585 ``The Notorious Bettie Page,'' helped introduce her to a new generation in the United States and abroad.
4 1 36 4586 ``She was reclusive and private, so without intending to be, without quite understanding how, her modeling work made her a pivotal figure in the sexual revolution that began in the 1950s,'' Roesler said.
4 10 1 4587 Bettie Page, the 1950s pinup and bondage model who provided more than a half-century of inspiration for everybody from Madonna to the Suicide Girls to artist Olivia De Berardinis (as well as having her image used on all sorts of merchandise), <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> yesterday in Los Angeles at the age of 85.
4 10 2 4588 Born in Nashville, Page left her job as a schoolteacher and secretary to begin a career in modeling in 1950.
4 10 3 4589 Throughout the 50s, she appeared clad in leopard print bikinis, black leather, and wielding whips in publications like Wink and Titter.
4 10 4 4590 In 1955, she appeared in a Christmas spread for Playboy.
4 10 5 4591 She had appeared in thousands of photos when she abruptly walked away from her career at the age of 35.
4 10 6 4592 In 1995, Page was summoned to testify before the U.S. Senate at anti-pornography hearings.
4 10 7 4593 She moved to Florida shortly thereafter, became a born-again Christian, suffered a nervous breakdown, and was diagnosed as a schizophrenic.
4 10 8 4594 But her legend grew over the years, as her image kept reappearing in popular culture.
4 10 9 4595 She was the inspiration for a character in Dale Stevens' 1982 comic series The Rocketeer, and the 1991 movie based on the series had actress Jennifer Connolly in the Page-inspired role.
4 10 10 4596 Artist Olivia De Berardinis also immortalized Page in several paintings, which have become popular tattoos among modern day rockabilly and goth girls.
4 10 11 4597 Page learned of her career resurgence after being released from a mental hospital in 1992.
4 10 12 4598 Bettie Page T-shirts, posters, watches, wallets, and more were hot-sellers, and although Page refused to have her picture taken the last two decades of her life, she embraced her legacy and occasionally did meet-and-greet signings at events throughout the U.S. and gave her blessing to an official Web site, www.bettiepage.com.
4 10 13 4599 Page had been hospitalized for the past three weeks for pneumonia.
4 10 14 4600 She was scheduled to be released December 2, but suffered a heart attack.
4 10 15 4601 Her health never recovered, and she passed at away at 6: 41 last night.
4 10 16 4602 A number of sites have already posted tributes to Page.
4 10 17 4603 You can check out the tributes in the L.A. Times, at MTV.com, and also at Page's official site.
4 11 1 4604 Bettie Page, the 1950s pin-up queen and pop culture icon who <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> on Thursday, will be remembered for her indomitable influence on style, fashion, and sexual expression.
4 11 2 4605 But as Bettie's biographer -- and the only one with whom she ever cooperated -- I can tell you that the underground bondage queen also had the unlikely effect of thematically shaping a series of biographical and highly feminist novels about powerful women in history.
4 11 3 4606 In 1991, intrigued by the resurgence of Bettie's image in venues as diverse as rockabilly clubs, nostalgia rags, and S&M fashion gone mainstream, I wrote a cover story for the L.A. Weekly, ``In Search of Bettie Page.''
4 11 4 4607 For nine months, I had tracked down anyone who had ever known her or photographed her.
4 11 5 4608 But Bettie herself, the object of much speculation, remained elusive.
4 11 6 4609 Most people thought she was dead.
4 11 7 4610 Then, as fate would have it, someone gave Bettie, who was living in anonymity and seclusion, a copy of the article.
4 11 8 4611 Imagine the shock -- a seventy-something senior citizen who ran away from it all forty years prior, suddenly finds that she is famous again.
4 11 9 4612 But she liked it.
4 11 10 4613 Though she did not want to re-enter the public arena, Bettie sent me a letter praising the piece, calling us ``kindred spirits.''
4 11 11 4614 Soon, with co-author James Swanson, I embarked on the adventure of writing her biography, sitting down with her for hundreds of hours while she told us her story.
4 11 12 4615 At the time, I was also trying to work out how to tell the stories of women in history who had been either dropped from the record or misinterpreted through the sexist lens of their biographers.
4 11 13 4616 I was to start with Kleopatra (the original Greek spelling), a victim of Roman propaganda remembered for the men with whom she slept rather than for her diplomacy, leadership, and the fact that she had mastered nine languages.
4 11 14 4617 How to present the stories of women who had been victimized without writing a victim story, I kept asking myself?
4 11 15 4618 How to give women in history who had been reduced to their sexuality the full breadth of their experience without diminishing or demeaning their sexuality?
4 11 16 4619 So here was Bettie Page, a woman known only for her sexuality, who had been sexually abused by her father, sexually violated by a gang of strangers, and emotionally battered by a husband.
4 11 17 4620 In the years since she had gone underground, Bettie had become a born-again Christian working for the Billy Graham Crusade.
4 11 18 4621 Surely she would repudiate the work she'd done as a pin-up and bondage model.
4 11 19 4622 Surely she saw herself as a victim of the patriarchy that hijacked her beauty and sensuality and exploited it for its own gratification.
4 11 20 4623 Surely I was about to meet a woman who considered herself a victim.
4 11 21 4624 I was wrong.
4 11 22 4625 Despite her more unfortunate experiences, Bettie never presented herself as a casualty of sexual abuse, and she never used that, or her religious beliefs, which were strong, to renounce the work she'd done as a model.
4 11 23 4626 Moreover, she never denounced sexual expression.
4 11 24 4627 ``God created us naked,'' she said by way of explaining her total lack of inhibition in the buff.
4 11 25 4628 She purported that bondage modeling ``was such fun,'' even at times ``hilarious,'' except for when the elaborate gear became uncomfortable.
4 11 26 4629 And sex itself, she assured me on many occasions, was for her, always pleasurable and joyful.
4 11 27 4630 Though she had at times suffered at their hands, she never expressed bitterness toward men.
4 11 28 4631 I know women who are resoundingly more hostile than Bettie Page just for having suffered a few bad dates.
4 11 29 4632 No, Bettie was not going to allow anyone or anything to diminish the joy she experienced when she put that corset on (or took it off) and felt her full-blown sexual power.
4 11 30 4633 Since the publication of Bettie Page: Life of a Pin-Up Legend, I have published four historical novels with strong female characters.
4 11 31 4634 Each, in her own way, was a victim, either of the era in which she lived and its laws, or of individual abusers, or of the general abuses and oppressive nature of the culture at large.
4 11 32 4635 Despite the enormous consciousness-raising of the last few decades, we still see attempts to diminish today's female powerbrokers women like Hillary Clinton or Sarah Palin by sexualizing them.
4 11 33 4636 Yes, in our porn-saturated society, people are still trying to shame women for -- what?
4 11 34 4637 Having sexual attributes?
4 11 35 4638 At least we can point to one woman, Bettie Page, who wouldn't have it.
4 11 36 4639 Bettie's obits paint a bleak picture of her later years.
4 11 37 4640 But I found that, despite her trials, she had retained a zest for life and always took pleasure in memories of the work that she'd done.
4 11 38 4641 I hope that Bettie is remembered for her sexual joy, and for the gleeful spirit she brought to sexual imagery, whether she was frolicking on the beach or being ball-gagged and spanked, rather than for being a victim.
4 11 39 4642 A female friend of mine said this morning, ``Bettie Page did more for sexual expression than Alfred Kinsey.'' Amen, sister.
4 11 40 4643 For all the countless (and valuable) mountains of scholarly and feminist writing that have influenced my thinking and my portrayal of women, I still look to a lady who said it all by looking into the camera and defying anyone to tell her she was bad or wrong.
4 11 41 4644 Amen to you, too, Bettie.
4 11 42 4645 Rest in peace.
4 12 1 4646 Yesterday in Los Angeles, pin-up icon Bettie Page <MENTION CHAIN="1">succumbed</MENTION> to complications from a heart <MENTION CHAIN="3">attack</MENTION>  <MENTION CHAIN="3">suffered</MENTION> almost three weeks ago.
4 12 2 4647 Few women in modern history have incited such lust and reverence in men and women alike.
4 12 3 4648 To the rockabilly culture, she embodied the ideal woman - voluptuous and healthy, with that leveling sneer.
4 12 4 4649 She seemed to dare you to not stare at her.
4 12 5 4650 Her hairstyle launched a thousand girls to slice off their bangs and get out the black dye.
4 12 6 4651 Literally tens of thousands of women are walking around today as perfect Bettie clones of all shapes and sizes.
4 12 7 4652 With her nude photoshoots, the bondage angle and her defiance in the face of censorship, she was a precursor to the '70s feminist movement - '50s punk rock in heels and garters.
4 12 8 4653 Page has been the inspiration for dozens of songs all across the musical landscape, but it was the rockabilly guys that took to her the most; not to mention female-fronted bands like the Horrorpops or even pop's Katy Perry.
4 12 9 4654 Even Amy Winehouse's look in the beginning was a derivative of Page.
4 13 1 4655 She was the wholesome face of America's kinky secret -- even if no one saw that face for half a century.
4 13 2 4656 Bettie Page, the notorious Southern gal-turned-dominatrix-turned pin-up-queen-turned born again Christian, <MENTION CHAIN="1">died</MENTION> Thursday at age 85.
4 13 3 4657 The details of her death are known:
4 13 4 4658 She had been hospitalized in Los Angeles for four weeks due to pneumonia, only to suffer from a heart attack.
4 13 5 4659 Far less is known of her life -- at least the last five decades of it.
4 13 6 4660 In 1957, Page disappeared from the flash of the cameras and the public spotlight.
4 13 7 4661 She'd found religion, became a recluse, and lost contact with friends and associates.
4 13 8 4662 But in the short time she donned panties and garters, brandished a whip and a whip-smart attitude, she was the queen of kink.
4 13 9 4663 Page, you see, was to erotica what Elvis was to rock 'n' roll.
4 13 10 4664 No, she wasn't the first pin-up.
4 13 11 4665 She wasn't even the best looking.
4 13 12 4666 But she had ``that thing'' that could take what was once a dark art form into the American mainstream.
4 13 13 4667 Unlike Elvis, though, Page never got bloated.
4 13 14 4668 She checked out in her prime.
4 13 15 4669 She didn't even allow to have her photo taken.
4 13 16 4670 She remained frozen in time.
4 13 17 4671 Yet, her image continues to strut its black stilettos through pop culture.
4 13 18 4672 ``Bettie Page'' remains short-hand for a haircut, an image and a cult that includes everyone and everything -- from designer Vivienne Westwood to rockabilly hounds to hot-rodders, comic books, Madonna, Goths, neo-burlesque performers and devil-may-care types.
4 13 19 4673 The Nashville, Tenn., girl never imagined she'd ever stir such a fuss.
4 13 20 4674 ``She looked so fresh and wholesome,'' said Bunny Yeager, whose photographs of Page appeared in virtually every men's magazine in the nineteen fifties.
4 13 21 4675 ``She wasn't trying to be seductive; she was the girl next door.''
4 13 22 4676 One big difference between Page and most neighbors, said Yeager:
4 13 23 4677 ``She felt more comfortable in the nude than in clothes.''
4 13 24 4678 Her story of unintentional notoriety began in 1950, when she boarded a Greyhound bound for Manhattan.
4 13 25 4679 Within months, her innocent face and curvy body made her the hit of the ``camera-club circuit.''
4 13 26 4680 ``Back then, you'd have a bunch of guys with cameras travel by bus to private houses to photograph girls,'' Yeager said.
4 13 27 4681 An aesthetic was born, one that mixed mundane suburbia with raw sexuality.
4 13 28 4682 By 1952, Page was breaking taboos, posing with a ball strapped in her mouth, whip in hand and devilish look on face -- in photos and movies that featured stripping, spanking and faux lesbianism that straddled burlesque and pornography.
4 13 29 4683 Page was hardly tawdry, though, Yeager said.
4 13 30 4684 ``She was so at ease, so wholesome.''
4 13 31 4685 The traits made a Page a natural in natural settings captured by Yeager, who met Page in 1954.
