4 7 14 4871 Early Years
4 7 15 4872 Bettie Mae Page was born on April 22, 1923, in Nashville, Tennessee.
4 7 16 4873 The second of six children, she helped raise her younger siblings while the family traveled around the U.S. in search of work.
4 7 17 4874 Page's mother placed her daughters in an orphanage after divorcing her husband, who was sentenced to two years in an Atlanta penitentiary for stealing a policeman's car.
4 7 18 4875 At the age of 10, Page began to mimic actresses and perform songs for the other girls at the orphanage before her mother, who worked as a hairdresser during the day and in a laundry at night, reclaimed her children after a year.
4 7 19 4876 Page took refuge from her traumatic family life in local community centers, where she learned to cook, sew and study hard enough to top her class at high school.
4 7 20 4877 She was a member of the drama club, helped edit the school newspaper and was voted ``The Most Likely to Succeed.''
4 7 21 4878 She won a $100 scholarship to Peabody College in Nashville, where she graduated with a Bachelor of Arts degree in education.
4 7 22 4879 Three Husbands
4 7 23 4880 In February 1943, she married Billy Neal, the first of her three husbands, and moved to San Francisco, where she had her first modeling assignment for a local furrier.
4 7 24 4881 While Neal served in the Mariana Islands during World War II, Page lived in Nashville, Miami and Port au Prince, Haiti.
4 7 25 4882 In 1947, she filed for divorce and moved to New York.
4 7 26 4883 Three years later while walking on Coney Island, she met police officer Jerry Tibbs who had an interest in photography and assembled Page's first portfolio.
4 7 27 4884 Tibbs introduced her to camera clubs, men's hobbyist groups that sometimes acted as a front for erotic photography, and Page's career took off.
4 7 28 4885 She then appeared in publisher Robert Harrison's girlie magazines Wink, Flirt and Beauty Parade.
4 7 29 4886 In January 1955, she was the centerfold model in Hugh Hefner's fledgling Playboy magazine, one month before actress Jayne Mansfield appeared as the publication's Playmate.
4 7 30 4887 ``She had a saucy innocence that is both contemporary and provocative, and also nostalgic,'' Hefner said.
4 7 31 4888 Media Mogul
4 7 32 4889 Page, who claimed she ignored media mogul Howard Hughes's request for a screen test in 1955 because she didn't want to sleep with him, also studied acting under Herbert Berghoff at Sea Cliff Summer Theater on Long Island.
4 7 33 4890 The apprenticeship helped her gain parts in New York stage productions and on television, once appearing on ``The Jackie Gleason Show.''
4 7 34 4891 Some of her most celebrated snapshots were taken in 1954 during a session with photographer Bunny Yeager at the Africa USA wildlife park in Boca Raton, Florida.
4 7 35 4892 They included nude poses with two cheetahs and scenes in a leopard-patterned jungle outfit that she made herself.
4 7 36 4893 Her ``Dark Angel'' image stemmed from bondage and fetish sessions for Irving Klaw's Movie Star News.
4 7 37 4894 Klaw, who paid $80 for four hours' work at his studio in Greenwich Village, New York, required sadomasochistic shots to meet the demand of high- profile, educated clients.
4 7 38 4895 His sister Paula created the sets and helped Page develop the fetish image.
4 7 39 4896 'Very Sweet'
4 7 40 4897 ``Paula was one of the nicest women I've ever known in my life,'' Page said.
4 7 41 4898 ``Only Paula was allowed to tie us up.
4 7 42 4899 She was very gentle, caring and considerate.
4 7 43 4900 She never tied any ropes too tight.
4 7 44 4901 She was very sweet.''
4 7 45 4902 A Congressional investigation initiated by Tennessee Senator Estes Kefauver in 1955 called Page as a witness and put Klaw out of business, though he had no case to answer because his models were never nude.
4 7 46 4903 The evidence of obscenity had included more- explicit poses that Page had done for camera clubs after a drinking session one night at a party.
4 7 47 4904 The Congressional probe is said to have contributed to her decision to give up modeling.
4 7 48 4905 Throughout the 1960s, Page attended Bible schools in Los Angeles, Chicago and Oregon, helping teenage mothers and visiting jails.
4 7 49 4906 Her breakdown in 1972 after divorcing third husband Harry Lear led to four months' treatment in Florida's Jackson Memorial Hospital and 20 months in Patton State Hospital in San Bernardino, California.
4 7 50 4907 She also had numerous run-ins with the law, including a charge of assault with a deadly weapon after brandishing a knife at her landlady who didn't provide Page with rent receipts.
4 7 51 4908 Pop-Culture Revival
4 7 52 4909 Page's pop-culture revival emanated from artwork by Robert Blue and Olivia de Berardinis, who drew on her fantasy and fetish work.
4 7 53 4910 David Stevens also featured Page in ``The Rocketeer'' comics from the early 1980s, prompting an avalanche of similar publications based on her persona.
4 7 54 4911 In later years, she lived in California and collected royalties from her work as a model after signing with Curtis Management Group.
4 7 55 4912 In 2005, Time Warner Inc. and HBO Films released ``The Notorious Bettie Page,'' a feature film starring Gretchen Mol as Page.
4 7 56 4913 Page avoided the camera lens after her modeling years, though she was photographed with Hefner at Playboy's 50th anniversary celebration in 2003.
4 7 57 4914 ``I want people to remember me as I was,'' she said in a Playboy interview in 1998.
4 7 58 4915 Page was divorced three times and had no children.
