40 8 6 5162 But much to our disappointment, the 17-incher is shipping with a plain ol' dual-core (Core 2 Duo) chip.
40 8 7 5163 True, at 2.66 GHz it's slightly faster than the other MacBook Pros.
40 8 8 5164 But there are hardly any substantial changes to justify the longer wait for this notebook.
40 8 9 5165 Apple was able to beef up the MacBook Pro's battery by taking advantage of the generous amount of space available in the notebook's enclosure.
40 8 10 5166 This battery is also non-removable, which Apple said was necessary to use as much space as possible.
40 8 11 5167 Apple also claims the new MacBook Pro's battery is more environmentally friendly because it lasts five years and has fewer toxins.
40 8 12 5168 Looks like our Apple source, and several others in various blogs, were incorrect about the rumor of a new Mac Mini launching at Macworld.
40 8 13 5169 We'll look into the reasons why and provide an update soon.
40 9 1 5170 For me the new, unibody MacBook Pro 17-inch (PN MB604LL/A) is probably the most exciting thing <MENTION CHAIN="3">announced</MENTION> here at Macworld Expo.
40 9 2 5171 Not only because I'm more of a hardware guy but also because I'm a MacBook freak.
40 9 3 5172 So, where to start?
40 9 4 5173 The MBP has three compelling new features.
40 9 5 5174 The new MBP17 has a matte screen option.
40 9 6 5175 Can I get a Hallelujah?!
40 9 7 5176 I've been a staunch critic of glossy displays in MacBooks, and I'm not the only one.
40 9 8 5177 It appears that Cupertino is finally listening.
40 9 9 5178 The unibody MacBook Pro 17 is the first in the new form-factor MacBooks to offer a configuration with a matte screen Apple calls ``antiglare.''
40 9 10 5179 It's a $50 option though, which is a bit of a slap in the face.
40 9 11 5180 If I'm spending $2,800 on a notebook computer you'd think that Apple would throw in the matte screen option.
40 9 12 5181 But at least it's available, which is excellent.
40 9 13 5182 The question that remains is if the matte screen option will trickle down to the MBP15 and even the MB13.
40 9 14 5183 Representatives in the Apple booth didn't know the answer when I asked them today.
40 9 15 5184 The new MBP17 can support up to 8GB of maximum RAM (and has 4GB standard) which is a huge step in the right direction.
40 9 16 5185 If you can get past the 8GB $1,200 sticker price, that is.
40 9 17 5186 I'm sure that the RAM price is so high because the new 17 ships with two, 2GB 1066MHz DDR3 SDRAM modules and both have to be removed and replaced with two, 4GB modules to get to 8GB.
40 9 18 5187 Prices will eventually come down and 8GB is an attractive option for memory hungry applications and anything to do with virtualization.
40 9 19 5188 The MBP17's fixed battery is a bit of a scandal.
40 9 20 5189 It's as if Apple didn't learn its lesson with the MacBook Air and iPhone batteries.
40 9 21 5190 After watching the video by the battery engineers during today's keynote, I'm partially convinced.
40 9 22 5191 Their justification is that fixed batteries save a lot of room previously occupied by connectors, latches and doors.
40 9 23 5192 A fixed battery can use more internal real estate in the enclosure to store power - goes the refrain. As a result the MBP17 fixed battery holds 40 percent more energy and will last up to 8 hours on a charge (7 hours when using the faster NVIDIA 9600M GT chip) according to Apple.
40 9 24 5193 I'm curious about the real-world run times though.
40 9 25 5194 Most companies base their battery benchmarks on perfect world conditions and it will be interesting to see how long the new battery really lasts.
40 9 26 5195 The third USB port is a welcome addition but it comes at the expense of a dedicated FW400 port on the previous model.
40 9 27 5196 Solid State Drives (SSDs) are now available as 128MB (+$500) and 256MB (+$900) options.
40 9 28 5197 In case you're wondering, a maxed out MBP17 configuration (2.93GHz, 8GB, 256GB SSD and anti-glare) will set you back $5,250. 
40 9 29 5198 Start saving your nickels and dimes, kids.
40 9 30 5199 I'm going to wait and see if the anti-glare screen trickles down to the MBP 15-inch before diving in, although the 8GB of RAM is attractive.
