44 1 1 5736 Can EDS Remain Vendor-Neutral Under HP` s Thumb?
44 1 2 5737 Will EDS remain open-minded about obtaining products and services from other vendors?
44 1 3 5738 Industry analysts contacted by eWEEK generally say they believe that Hewlett-Packard's forthcoming $13.9 billion <MENTION CHAIN="1">acquisition</MENTION> of Electronic Data Systems? <MENTION CHAIN="2">announced</MENTION> officially on May 13 is a good move for both companies, although there will be the usual integration snafus over vendor neutrality issues, business lines, culture shock and layoffs.
44 1 4 5739 Analysts have also said it is a good move overall for customers and potential customers, because the combined company will offer them a greater palette of products and services from which to choose.
44 1 5 5740 A combined HP-EDS will certainly put a new kind of pressure on IT services leader IBM.
44 1 6 5741 IBM's $54 billion-per-year Global Services arm-by far the largest in the world-will start to feel the heat from the combined HP-EDS entity, which will start out at a net worth of $38 billion per year.
44 1 7 5742 For high-end enterprise IT services before this <MENTION CHAIN="1">merger</MENTION>, the market consisted of IBM and everybody else.
44 1 8 5743 IT Swiss army knife is all can openers
44 1 9 5744 The biggest unanswered question on people's minds involved vendor neutrality for EDS and its current customers.
44 1 10 5745 EDS for years was a sort of IT Swiss army knife in that it used whatever products and services from other vendors were needed to complete its job correctly and within budget constraints.
44 1 11 5746 With its impending new ownership by one of those key vendors, that picture may change.
44 1 12 5747 ``We don't know what will happen with EDS' vendor neutrality,'' Rick Sturm, founder and president of Enterprise Management Associates, told eWEEK.
44 1 13 5748 Overall, my take is that this <MENTION CHAIN="1">transaction</MENTION> sounds great in theory, but there many potential pitfalls.
44 1 14 5749 This is one of them.
44 1 15 5750 For example, EDS has largely standardized on management software from CA.
44 1 16 5751 Will they migrate to HP software now?
44 1 17 5752 That would take a long time and a lot of money,'' Sturm said.
44 1 18 5753 ``On the other hand, it doesn't make sense to help support a competitor with license and maintenance fees.
44 1 19 5754 That is just one small point regarding neutrality.''
44 1 20 5755 EDS, in fact, has a large current contract with CA for network and systems management in direct competition to HP's OpenView.
44 1 21 5756 CA had no immediate comment May 13.
44 1 22 5757 At least initially, Sturm said, there will be little noticeable impact on customers from the <MENTION CHAIN="1">deal</MENTION>.
44 1 23 5758 ``There will probably be some service impacts once the organizations truly merge and consolidate resources,'' he said.
44 1 24 5759 ``[HP CIO] Randy Mott has been driving data center consolidation and standardization.
44 1 25 5760 I expect that effort will be renewed with EDS.
44 1 26 5761 Disruptions are inevitable with such migrations.''
44 2 1 5762 Hewlett-Packard is negotiating to <MENTION CHAIN="1">buy</MENTION> technology services provider Electronic Data Systems in a <MENTION CHAIN="1">deal</MENTION> that could help the world's largest personal computer maker snap up more data management and consulting contracts.
44 2 2 5763 Palo Alto-based HP and Plano, Texas-based EDS confirmed the talks yesterday shortly after The Wall Street Journal reported a <MENTION CHAIN="1">deal</MENTION> could be reached as early as today.
44 2 3 5764 Citing unnamed people familiar with the matter, the Journal said HP will pay $12 billion to $13 billion - a price that translates to $24 to $26 per share.
44 2 4 5765 The companies declined to comment beyond their confirmation of the talks.
44 2 5 5766 EDS shares soared $5.27, or nearly 28 percent, to finish yesterday at $24.13.
44 2 6 5767 HP shares dropped $2.49, more than 5 percent, to close at $46.64 as investors fretted over the deal's logistics.
44 2 7 5768 HP ended January with nearly $10 billion in cash.
44 2 8 5769 With a market value of about $115 billion, HP could easily use its own stock to finance the <MENTION CHAIN="1">purchase</MENTION>.
44 2 9 5770 Like many corporate marriages, bringing together HP and EDS could trigger cultural clashes that ruin the union, said AMR Research analyst Dana Stiffler.
44 2 10 5771 ``Palo Alto versus Plano wrangling will destroy any short-medium-term benefit unless there's a strong integration road map,'' she predicted.
44 2 11 5772 If the <MENTION CHAIN="1">deal</MENTION> is completed, it would be HP's biggest acquisition since it bought Compaq Computer Corp. for $19 billion in 2002.
44 2 12 5773 HP has been trying to expand its technology consulting and data management business for years, hoping to challenge rival IBM's leadership in the lucrative field.
44 2 13 5774 In 2000, HP attempted to buy PricewaterhouseCoopers' consulting division before those discussions unraveled.
44 2 14 5775 IBM wound up buying PricewaterhouseCoopers' consulting arm instead.
44 2 15 5776 The demand for technology consulting and customer support services has steadily grown during the past two decades as the automation of corporate America and the rise of the Internet prompted more businesses to hire outside help to help ensure all the computer software and hardware runs smoothly.
44 2 16 5777 IBM's technology services division brought in revenue of $54 billion last year, accounting for half of the company's total sales.
44 2 17 5778 Combined, EDS and HP's technology services division had about $39 billion in revenue last year.
44 2 18 5779 <MENTION CHAIN="1">Acquiring</MENTION> EDS also could yield more government work for HP, which had about $500 million in prime federal contracts in fiscal 2007.
44 2 19 5780 EDS is far better connected, with deals worth about $2.5 billion - putting it among the top 10 among government technology contractors.
44 2 20 5781 Combined, HP and EDS still would lag significantly behind government contractors such as Lockheed Martin Corp. and Boeing Company.
44 2 21 5782 EDS earned $716 million on $22.1 billion in revenue last year.
44 2 22 5783 The Texas company has been linked with possible deals previously, including a reported interest by Deutsche Telekom late last year and Dell before that.
44 2 23 5784 None of the companies ever confirmed reports that they were talking.
44 2 24 5785 Former IBM salesman H. Ross Perot left IBM to start EDS in 1962 and practically invented the business of running other companies' computer systems, now called information-technology or IT services.
44 2 25 5786 Perot sold EDS to General Motors for $2.5 billion in 1984 and eventually became so disillusioned with how that deal worked out that he sold his remaining EDS shares to the carmaker so he could start a rival service bearing his name.
44 2 26 5787 GM spun off EDS as an independent company in 1996 and remained its largest customer.
44 2 27 5788 EDS was riding high at the start of the decade, despite the dot-com bubble's bursting.
44 2 28 5789 But in late 2002, earnings shortfalls led to investor lawsuits, a Securities and Exchange Commission investigation, the ouster of the chief executive and a sharp drop in the stock price.
44 2 29 5790 The company lost $1.7 billion in 2003, but it gradually righted itself under CEO Michael Jordan, a retired CBS and Westinghouse CEO who was hired to lead a turnaround.
44 2 30 5791 Jordan fixed some money-losing contracts, including a multibillion-dollar deal to build a communications network for the Navy and Marine Corps, and began cutting costs by sending thousands of jobs to low-cost countries such as India.
