7 6 1 6276 The major heavyweight year ended much as it started, with Wladimir Klitschko owning the division against overmatched opposition, and with Hasim Rahman being nothing but a shell of the man that once shockingly knocked out Lennox Lewis.
7 6 2 6277 Klitschko <MENTION CHAIN="1">dominated</MENTION> Rahman over six-plus rounds, <MENTION CHAIN="4">knocking</MENTION> him down in a horribly one-sided sixth round and then <MENTION CHAIN="5">landing</MENTION> enough hard blows early in the seventh for referee Tony Weeks to step in and call an <MENTION CHAIN="6">end</MENTION> to it.
7 6 3 6278 That should just about do it for the 36-year old Rahman, who hasn't scored an impressive or notable win since 2005.
7 6 4 6279 Since that win over Monte Barrett, Rahman has gone 4-2-1 with a no-contest, beating nothing but club fighters, and often not even looking good doing that.
7 6 5 6280 He's had a long, strange career, and it looks like it's over at the top tier.
7 6 6 6281 He was so thoroughly overmatched tonight and unwilling to fight Klitschko that he's clearly got nothing left as a top fighter.
7 6 7 6282 Klitschko will move on and fight Alexander Povetkin, Chris Arreola or David Haye sometime in March or April, I'd wager, and he should be a heavy, heavy favorite against any of them.
7 6 8 6283 Arreola was hurt by Travis Walker, Povetkin just doesn't strike me as capable of being a truly top-notch guy, and Haye was shaken by Monte Barrett a bit even though he did basically dominate.
7 6 9 6284 I'd love to see Klitschko-Haye simply because I think Haye will make Wlad work.
7 6 10 6285 I said during the fight that this was yet another case of Klitschko fighting up or down to his opponent.
7 6 11 6286 Haye would make him fight up. 
7 6 12 6287 Rahman had him fighting down.
7 6 13 6288 The fight as also yet another example of why people crap on heavyweight fighting.
7 6 14 6289 It wasn't interesting, wasn't competitive, and you clearly had one guy (Rahman) not in shape to fight for more than five rounds.
7 6 15 6290 And worse than that, he didn't even fight.
7 6 16 6291 In the sixth, he landed one punch.
7 6 17 6292 He spent a lot of time laying on the ropes starting in the third round, barely punching at all.
7 6 18 6293 The HBO team today was Lampley, Kellerman and Lennox, and they did their usual bit when they watch a heavyweight fight with Lennox in the booth, which means they made verbal love to Lewis while Lewis agreed with their assessment of him as better than everyone fighting today.
7 6 19 6294 They're right, of course -- but we all know that.
7 6 20 6295 There was even one round where Lennox decided, out loud, that he is better than Wladimir Klitschko.
7 6 21 6296 As always, an interesting group that teaches me a lot about the fights I'm watching.
